commit_message:
Removing SymmetricKey docs from key module

This change removes the SymmetricKey class references from the key
module doc string. The SymmetricKey class resides in it's own module
and the key module only contains the Key class.

Change-Id: Ic93971584b6bdee5db0042ce8473225f2589a856

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: I52848a1f63cb4a1b30d9e1c32f4bb18c5d9fe80e

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Icfc882db41883410f7b40fc5a22bfaae1a65dedc

commit_message:
Fixes to devstack plugin

MULTI_HOST is only needed for nova-network, we
can remove it from the example

Change-Id: Ie03ea1f90e23adfb0f796b01cf31787ec13389cb

commit_message:
Adds tempest re-install to API/CLI

Uninstall existing Tempest local repo and install from new source and with new
Tempest config file. If source/conf aren't supplied, retrieve from old env
instead of using default source. Copy old conf to temp location and after
installation copy back to verifier.

Implements: blueprint improve-tempest-manage-cli
Change-Id: I410dcc9b5df58213085f727dee3d7fefa0b72b81

[{'created': '2015-04-24 12:11:32.000000000', 'message': "Do not manage host entries by default

Diskimage-builder currently writes cloud-init config file which adds a
host entry mapping the hostname and FQDN to 127.0.0.1 into every image
built. This is probably useful for some use cases but not for all, so
images which want this done should do it in their own image elements, it
shouldn't be a part of diskimage-builder's `base` element.

Particular description of the problem this causes in TripleO follows:

We get hosts files like this:

    ::1     localhost       localhost.localdomain   localhost6      localhost6.localdomain6
    127.0.0.1       localhost       localhost.localdomain   localhost4      localhost4.localdomain4
    127.0.0.1       ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z.novalocal ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z

    # HEAT_HOSTS_START - Do not edit manually within this section!

    192.0.2.17 ov-rl5i5saoc6h-0-wfzcsrqo34p6-controller-m3hy26lhxavl ov-rl5i5saoc6h-0-wfzcsrqo34p6-controller-m3hy26lhxavl.novalocal
    192.0.2.15 ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z.novalocal

The duplicate hostname/FQDN entry for 127.0.0.1 and 192.0.2.15 confuses
Corosync, which then fails to start a cluster when using hostnames in
the config file instead of IPs.

commit_message:
Make managing hosts entries optional

Diskimage-builder currently writes cloud-init config file which adds a
host entry mapping the hostname and FQDN to 127.0.0.1 into every image
built. This is probably useful for some use cases but not for all, so we
now allow customizing the manage_etc_hosts value via
DIB_CLOUD_INIT_ETC_HOSTS variable and also not writing the config at all
if that variable is explicitly set to an empty string (currently the
default is 'localhost' but in the future the default will be empty
string).

Particular description of the problem this causes in TripleO follows:

We get hosts files like this:

    ::1     localhost       localhost.localdomain   localhost6      localhost6.localdomain6
    127.0.0.1       localhost       localhost.localdomain   localhost4      localhost4.localdomain4
    127.0.0.1       ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z.novalocal ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z

    # HEAT_HOSTS_START - Do not edit manually within this section!

    192.0.2.17 ov-rl5i5saoc6h-0-wfzcsrqo34p6-controller-m3hy26lhxavl ov-rl5i5saoc6h-0-wfzcsrqo34p6-controller-m3hy26lhxavl.novalocal
    192.0.2.15 ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z ov-rl5i5saoc6h-1-hj5tzsbrdv4c-controller-dy6nuyarqy5z.novalocal
    192.0.2.16 ov-rl5i5saoc6h-2-a6v7saxnivm5-controller-7jboskte34r7 ov-rl5i5saoc6h-2-a6v7saxnivm5-controller-7jboskte34r7.novalocal
    # HEAT_HOSTS_END

The duplicate hostname/FQDN entry for 127.0.0.1 and 192.0.2.15 confuses
Corosync, which then fails to start a cluster when using hostnames in
the config file instead of IPs.

Change-Id: Ia8582883f737548e2911d3f36a1943e5b236281b

commit_message:
Don't use scoping information for admin auth

The only place that admin_auth seems to be used here is gaining the
user_id for establishing a trust. Fetching a token for only the user_id
is not an operation that requires scoping to a project so request an
unscoped token here.

Change-Id: Id7c30ec2340addb30d5bd463891c9fdd9280009e

commit_message:
Two api tests for 'firewall insertion mode' feature

Some time ago the feature called 'fwaas insertion mode' was merged.
It allows to associate a firewall with routers.

The patchset adds two api tests:
* Create firewall assiciated with a router, add another router
to the firewall, remove old one
* Create firewall assoicited with a router, try to create new
firewall on the same router

Change-Id: I7c4d41189056ff6da47bc1173d3479183e58a173

Ok so I'm getting doubtful.

The original idea was just to change the default regionOne case to make life easier for people who e.g. follow the Ubuntu install guide available in the docs (where it says regionOne everywhere, where all the defaults in config files have regionOne - except in Neutron's metadata_agent.ini).

Now I'm concerned that if I follow your suggestion to comment out all the auth_* admin_* lines it's going to break stuff like deployment tools which replace %SERVICE_FOO% and don't expect the lines to be commented out.

There are lots of inconsistencies found in OpenStack config files, and fixing that properly would require some advance and cross-project planning. This was not the goal of this patch."}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2015-04-02 16:02:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Use "regionOne" case in metadata agent conf

Set auth_region to "regionOne" instead of "RegionOne" as the provided
metadata agent default configuration in order to be consistent with docs
and avoid confusion for users.
Also, make it clear this is about the *Keystone* API.

Change-Id: I8f47be1b4b43defb86b4da2a34c5f40494361045

This change adds the ability to inject routes in interfaces.template
by injecting them in the template engine.

Routes are now found in each interface in the interfaces variable.

The following attributes are available for each route:
  * gateway (eg. 192.168.0.1)
  * cidr (eg. 192.168.10.0/24)
  * network (eg. 192.168.10.0)
  * netmask (eg. 255.255.255.0)

Note: Routes are not injected by default in interfaces.template.
This is to avoid any potential conflicts with existing network agents
such as dhcp, l3, etc.

See nova/tests/network/interfaces-override.template for an example
on how to interact with the new interface 'routes' attribute.

Blueprint: network-template-routes-injection
DocImpact: Routes are now available in the network template engine.
Change-Id: Ic22c8af721d539c8180b5caa7ba348e834ddbb56
"}, {'created': '2015-02-16 20:47:59.000000000', 'message': "Add ability to inject routes in interfaces.template

This change adds the ability to inject routes in interfaces.template
by injecting them in the template engine.

Routes are now found in each interface in the interfaces variable.

The following attributes are available for each route:
  * gateway (eg. 192.168.0.1)
  * cidr (eg. 192.168.10.0/24)
  * network (eg. 192.168.10.0)
  * netmask (eg. 255.255.255.0)

Example of how to inject routes in interfaces.template:

    {% for ifc in interfaces %}
    auto {{ ifc.name }}
    iface {{ ifc.name }} inet static
    # [...]
    {% for route in ifc.routes %}
        post-up ip route add {{ route.cidr }} via {{ route.gateway }} dev {{ ifc.name }}
        pre-down ip route del {{ route.cidr }} via {{ route.gateway }} dev {{ ifc.name }}
    {% endfor %}
    {% endfor %}

Note: Routes are not injected by default in interfaces.template.
This is to avoid any potential conflicts with existing network agents
such as dhcp, l3, etc.

See nova/tests/network/interfaces-override.template for a complete
example on how to interact with the new interface 'routes' attribute.

Blueprint: network-template-routes-injection
DocImpact: Routes are now available in the network template engine.
Change-Id: Ic22c8af721d539c8180b5caa7ba348e834ddbb56

"}, {'created': '2015-04-28 19:36:10.000000000', 'message': "Add ability to inject routes in interfaces.template

This change adds the ability to inject routes in interfaces.template
by injecting them in the template engine.

It adds support for injecting extra routes when instances are spawned
on networks that do not have DHCP or Neutron routers.

Routes are now found in each interface in the interfaces variable.

The following attributes are available for each route:
  * gateway (eg. 192.168.0.1)
  * cidr (eg. 192.168.10.0/24)
  * network (eg. 192.168.10.0)
  * netmask (eg. 255.255.255.0)

Example of how to inject routes in interfaces.template:

    {% for ifc in interfaces %}
    auto {{ ifc.name }}
    iface {{ ifc.name }} inet static
    # [...]
    {% for route in ifc.routes %}
        post-up ip route add {{ route.cidr }} via {{ route.gateway }} dev {{ ifc.name }}
        pre-down ip route del {{ route.cidr }} via {{ route.gateway }} dev {{ ifc.name }}
    {% endfor %}
    {% endfor %}

Note: Routes are not injected by default in interfaces.template.
This is to avoid any potential conflicts with existing network agents
such as dhcp, l3, etc.

See nova/tests/network/interfaces-override.template for a complete

commit_message:
Add ability to inject routes in interfaces.template

This change adds the ability to inject routes in interfaces.template
by injecting them in the template engine.

It adds support for injecting extra routes when instances are spawned
on networks that do not have DHCP or Neutron routers.

Routes are now found in each interface in the interfaces variable.

The following attributes are available for each route:
  * gateway (eg. 192.168.0.1)
  * cidr (eg. 192.168.10.0/24)
  * network (eg. 192.168.10.0)
  * netmask (eg. 255.255.255.0)

Example of how to inject routes in interfaces.template:

    {% for ifc in interfaces %}
    auto {{ ifc.name }}
    iface {{ ifc.name }} inet static
    # [...]
    {% for route in ifc.routes %}
        post-up ip route add {{ route.cidr }} via {{ route.gateway }} dev {{ ifc.name }}
        pre-down ip route del {{ route.cidr }} via {{ route.gateway }} dev {{ ifc.name }}
    {% endfor %}
    {% endfor %}

Note: Routes are not injected by default in interfaces.template.
This is to avoid any potential conflicts with existing network agents
such as dhcp, l3, etc.

See nova/tests/network/interfaces-override.template for a complete
example on how to interact with the new interface 'routes' attribute.

Blueprint: network-template-routes-injection
DocImpact: Routes are now available in the network template engine.
Change-Id: Ic22c8af721d539c8180b5caa7ba348e834ddbb56

commit_message:
Do not update nodes info on not ready nodes

If nodes are not ready or selected for deployemnt post_deployemnt
task for uploading nodes info and updating hosts should not be
executed on them.

Also fixed PEP8 warnings in files I've touched.

Change-Id: Icf2c51ec15f4028ff4da74a633481ca154e42d0a
Closes-Bug: #1450051

commit_message:
Fix InstanceList attribute of instance group to return List

Currently get_attr returns a string of all the ip addresses of the
instance group.This will change it to return a list of ip addresses.

Change-Id: Ic48d4d74ef7feb75a514f850f98f1544a3c06db3

commit_message:
Remove logging function from provision function block

It probably causes context switch in the thread in report_image_provision
function.

Change-Id: Ifcbf62dd10cf24eb20fca68cf47ed9852fb52480
Closes-Bug: #1453573

commit_message:
Denominator Agent

A new agent backend that uses denominator tool https://github.com/Netflix/denominator
to orchestrate resources of some DNSaaS providers (Dyn, Amazon, Rackspace etc.)

Change-Id: Ie871a0315816a1f395af6cb14a8be9f0dc62edbe

configure-vm: allow multiple baremetal-interface's

This patch updates the --baremetal-interface option such that

commit_message:
force the udp checksum for dhcp

The default vm setting assume udp checksums will be computed in
hardware. This fix forces the appliance to calculate the checksum for
DHCP replies.

This fix was inspired by the upstream reference implementation [1].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/148718/8/neutron/agent/linux/dhcp.py

Change-Id: Id5d4ecdb3ce803b4b2a571f9033a637b7818ee08

commit_message:
Allow libvirt to assign PCI slots for us

This patch updates scripts/configure-vm and the associated
vm.xml template so that we no longer manually assign PCI
slots. Libvirt will assign them automatically for us
and also do things like make sure memballoon is the last
slot as well.

This will help facilitate adding multiple network interfaces
without creating logic to handle the PCI slot assignments.

Change-Id: Ifa8e897ddde52a88e3b25ad267a196d3d9008bc3

Detach from non-func thread

Need to distinguish non-func and usb results in Testrail reports,
so removing thread_non_func_1_usb and create thread_non_func_1
and thread_usb threads

Backup driver for GlusterFS storage

An implementation of Cinder backup driver using GlusterFS as a
backend for Cinder backups.

[{'created': '2015-05-11 19:00:22.000000000', 'message': 'Make it clear the rfe tag is lower-case

This tripped me up, I tried adding RFE to my bug and was denied.
It seems the tag was added with lower-case letters.  This is fine with
me as it is consistent with most, if not all, other tags in the
project.  If it stays lower-case, we should at least make the quoted
tag in the policy document lower-case.

Change-Id: I9c72a2db2a168b56b1137839f5bfc1d2068d9f0c
'}]
commit_message:
Make it clear the rfe tag is lower-case

This tripped me up, I tried adding RFE to my bug and was denied.
It seems the tag was added with lower-case letters.  This is fine with
me as it is consistent with most, if not all, other tags in the
project.  If it stays lower-case, we should at least make the quoted
tag in the policy document lower-case.

Change-Id: I9c72a2db2a168b56b1137839f5bfc1d2068d9f0c

commit_message:
Split engine service test cases (3)

This patch separates out test cases related to software_config and
software_deployments into a standalone module. The patch also replaces a
few mox calls by mock calls.

commit_message:
Bump kombu and amqp requirements

We at least need these versions of amqp and kombu to have
a working heartbeat support.

Related-bug: #1436788
Closes-bug: #1436769
Closes-bug: #1408830

Change-Id: I61440c5ccf2b540fe9a1e868bdcae9f5d2cf8422

Add remaining_executions attribute to OS::Mistral::CronTrigger

remaining_executions defines the number of occurrences after
which the trigger should be deleted.

commit_message:
Use SHA256 instead of SHA1 for resource signature

SHA1 is not safe for signature, use sha256 instead.

Closes-Bug: #1447904

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Allow sink to create multiple entries per instance

There are a few situations where this may be useful, for
example simultaneous creation of

<hostname>.example.org
and
<instance-id>.example.org

The code already existed to clean up multiple entries for
a given host, so this change is pretty simple.

Co-Authored-By: Zhang Gengyuan <stanzgy@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I8a410107d970d079f757f9d22c44485856239517

blueprint ipv6-router (ChangeID:Iaefa95f788053ded9fc9c7ff6845c3030c6fd6df),
supports an IPv6 Router where the router gateway port has no subnet.

The BP implements the following. If an external network (without any subnet)
is attached to the Neutron router, it reads the ipv6_gateway config parameter
(LLA of upstream router) from l3_agent.ini file and adds a default route that
points to this LLA.  If the ipv6_gateway config value is not configured, it
would configure the gateway interface to accept router advts from upstream
router to build the default route.

For an HA router, we would have to configure keepalived to perform this
operation. This patch extends the functionality to an HA router.

Change-Id: I26dc5ce9e46c74423358aa8a9559bc6c7cbdf85e

commit_message:
Support BP:ipv6-router in Neutron HA Router

blueprint ipv6-router (ChangeID:Iaefa95f788053ded9fc9c7ff6845c3030c6fd6df),
supports an IPv6 Router where the router gateway port has no subnet.

The BP implements the following. If an external network (without any subnet)
is attached to the Neutron router, it reads the ipv6_gateway config parameter
(LLA of upstream router) from l3_agent.ini file and adds a default route that
points to this LLA.  If the ipv6_gateway config value is not configured, it
would configure the gateway interface to accept router advts from upstream
router to build the default route.

For an HA router, we would have to configure keepalived to perform this
operation. This patch extends the functionality to an HA router.

Implements: blueprint ipv6-router
Change-Id: I26dc5ce9e46c74423358aa8a9559bc6c7cbdf85e

commit_message:
lib/swift: the s3_token middleware should be provided by keystonemiddleware

Recently, keystoneclient.middleware has been moved from keystoneclient to
keystonemiddleware. The latter should be used.

Change-Id: Ib9489a21b988b32fc17399c08eeb60862efae034
Closes-Bug: #1452315

commit_message:
Assign GRE network to nodes in GRE tests

GRE network can be configured by the end user and
assigned to a physical interface. FuelWebClient has
been updated to reflect this.

Change-Id: I4d24d113caa23777c00dd945c6cfde1a683ee62a
Related-bug: #1285059

commit_message:
Add normal flow even when no router

Previously adding 2 VM to the same subnet without a router would not
install the internal subnet flow. This solves the issue.

Change-Id: I036587598e94013e7365c345379a0ce0d520df26

commit_message:
Changes Fuel release number for 6.1 documentation

Docker-related troubleshooting commands contain
incorrect Fuel release (6.0), though it should be
6.1.

This commit fixes the problem.

Change-Id: I2a66ba8cda79e972e9fa29f2d9b1a673c7017f53
Closes-Bug: 1442507

commit_message:
First pass at tempest_lib based functional testing

Begin moving tempest based CLI tests out of murano repo and into this
repo using tempest-lib. This patch adds the framework to run the functional
tests.

Use standard OpenStack environment variables to get keystone auth.

Change-Id: Ic0952dcf721a4d20378cc593d59a7c1e1e794cfc

commit_message:
Move unit tests into unit test directory

In order to pave the way for functional testing, move existing unit
tests into a directory labeled unit. A subsequent patch will add a
directory for functional tests.

Change-Id: I08e592c328104139386b1199cdc9c3aa9841805f

commit_message:
Remove H305 from tox.ini pep8 ignore list

H305 is about grouping imports. It seems like we meet the requirement. I
don't think there a reason to keep it.

Change-Id: Ia2ddd467288c3c3aad39aed98eefb532b0e1d280

subject: Properly re-raise exceptions in proxy_logging
messages:
[{'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-05-08 21:26:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2015-05-08 21:36:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Oh yeah, this is the old Eventlet problem where you do something monkeypatched (like network IO down in log_request), and your process trampolines to another greenthread for a while, and then when you come back your sys.exc_info() is gone.

I thought the latest Eventlet was going to fix this, but I guess not.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-08 22:14:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-swift-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/66/181566/1/check/gate-swift-pep8/1b1aa80/ : SUCCESS in 2m 22s

- check-swift-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/66/181566/1/check/check-swift-dsvm-functional/ccab747/ : SUCCESS in 23m 13s'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-11 09:40:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Based on reading this I'm wondering if it would be a good idea to delete exc_traceback in a 'finally' clause?"}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-11 09:51:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

...of course it would be helpful if I defined the 'this' i was reading ;) :

the note under sys.exc_info()

https://docs.python.org/2.7/library/sys.html#sys.exc_info"}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2015-05-11 18:54:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Alistair, I'm inclined to not bother, for two reasons: First, according to the note, the garbage collector will still properly reclaim exc_traceback. It may cause garbage collection to take a few more cycles, but there's no leak. Second, the rest of the Swift codebase behaves the same way, presumably to improve readability.

For examples, see https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/0997d2a/swift/proxy/controllers/base.py#L741-L763, https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/0997d2a/swift/common/utils.py#L1304, or https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/0997d2a/swift/common/internal_client.py#L187-L196. Additionally, there are places (like https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/master/swift/proxy/server.py#L568 or https://github.com/openstack/swift/blob/0997d2a/swift/common/utils.py#L2968) where we stuff the traceback into arbitrary places; at that point, we can't reasonably ensure the cycle gets broken."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-12 09:56:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

@Tim yes, I understood its not a leak just an (unquantified) efficiency, thanks for the pointers to precedent.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-12 09:56:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.

[{'created': '2015-05-08 21:26:31.000000000', 'message': 'Properly re-raise exceptions in proxy_logging

Previously, this could encounter TypeErrors, presumably because
sys.exc_clear() was called somewhere in the block of code between
catching the exception and re-raising.

Related-Bug: 1181146
Change-Id: Iadeea3f61e70bf83dc0eb063fdb27edd16f3ca32
'}]
commit_message:
Properly re-raise exceptions in proxy_logging

Previously, this could encounter TypeErrors, presumably because
sys.exc_clear() was called somewhere in the block of code between
catching the exception and re-raising.

Related-Bug: 1181146
Change-Id: Iadeea3f61e70bf83dc0eb063fdb27edd16f3ca32

commit_message:
Fix delete volume and improved conductor coverage

The JSONListType was not properly handling the remove call that made the
volume references removed from the actual list but present in the
database.

The coverage of conductor api improved.

Change-Id: I2ce346f5f388f59583a650e42a2af224fb7bda2d

I'd really like to see constraints on the record type field to record types outlined in some reasonable subset of DNS RFC's. For example, AXFR and IXFR are *technically* record types, but any user setting them in designate is almost certainly up to no good."}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-05-04 09:09:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ryan Brown. Thanks for reviewing. while writing this spec I tried to make sure that its inline with designate api http://designate.readthedocs.org/en/latest/rest/v1/records.html and its python client. And designate API does not have any constrain for the record type. so i have not added any.

But based on your input, i feel that designate should be exposing such a constrain over its ReST API, which is missing now, as the record type is controlled by designate and not by heat. Once designate expose such a constrain, then we can patch heat with it new constrain. So could kindly suggest the same to designate. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 12321, 'date': '2015-05-04 13:05:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Unfortunately they don't explicitly state in their API documentation what record types are supported, but I read their code and the recordset type only supports A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, SRV, TXT, SPF, NS, PTR, SSHFP, and SOA[1].

Any other record raises (internally to them) InvalidObject, which sends back a 400 status code. We can use the schemas there to make Heat raise errors during validation, instead of waiting for Designate to fail the create. 

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/325a3b651b77d5067498afdca360c21a9cf697eb/designate/objects/recordset.py#L94-L102"}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-05-04 15:24:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ryan Brown, Thanks a lot for actively look at the code. I wanted to check the code but stopped myself as there is no documentation available for this supported record type.

In heat, we usually don't support un-documented  feature but i think this one we could enable as it brings only the constrain validation.  So I would like to take opinion from core reviewers before bringing this constrain in the spec."}, {'account_id': 12321, 'date': '2015-05-04 15:35:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I'm not sure I'd call it an "undocumented feature", their API docs state that "400 Invalid Object" is a response to record creation, it just doesn't spell out the allowed record types in that document.'}, {'account_id': 12259, 'date': '2015-05-05 08:22:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

IMO, constraint validation is a critical step and helps user avoid failing stacks. It might be worth considering that we validate the record type. But unless there is an API support on what type of records are supported, it wouldn't be worth doing. We might add the currently supported types as constraint, but then we will have to keep track of new record types being added in newer versions of designate. IMO, it is worth waiting for an API from designate for this."}, {'account_id': 12259, 'date': '2015-05-05 12:05:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-05-05 12:23:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Mostly ok, couple questions inline'}, {'account_id': 12321, 'date': '2015-05-05 12:32:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-05-05 12:50:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 12259, 'date': '2015-05-06 03:14:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I had a chat with Designate folks on IRC and there indeed is no way to know supported record types. So, I have added a BP in Designate: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/designate/+spec/expose-api-for-supported-record-type

IMO, we should not wait for this to be implemented.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-05-06 05:41:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(3 comments)

Anant, Thanks for filing the blueprint on the Designate. 
Ryan, at this moment, I believe, we could go ahead without placing the constrain in place and once designate brings the blueprint into live, we could add it latter into designate plug-in.'}, {'account_id': 12321, 'date': '2015-05-06 12:10:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Anant, thank you for working with the Designate team and letting them know what we needed.

Kanagaraj, I agree, we shouldn't hold up this spec for that API endpoint in designate."}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-05-07 00:10:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-07 00:16:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Fix tests in Nailgun's master

After merging I56491481217910ec5c0e5403eb93800c47911c4f the master's
tests were broken. That happened because the patch wasn't rebased on
latest master and therefore CI was passed successfully.

Closes-Bug: #1454176

Signed-off-by: Igor Kalnitsky <igor@kalnitsky.org>

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-11 07:59:59.000000000', 'message': 'Fix 'AllocType' read failure in Huawei driver

The 'AllocType' have two values: Thin and Thick.
The following piece of code in the Huawei driver has
incorrect path and as a result the 'AllocType' is always
'None'. The correct values should be "Thin" or "Thick"
only.

'fstype = root.findtext('FILESYSTEM/AllocType')'

In code line 366: '"ALLOCTYPE": 1'
The "Thin" is set as the initial value. If the 'AllocType'
is always 'None', the 'AllocType' can not set as "Thick".

Change 'FILESYSTEM/AllocType' to 'Filesystem/AllocType' in
Huawei driver to avoid 'AllocType' can not be read out.

Change-Id: I63b77b8608b313729159d5732a5dae00cbe67034
Closes-Bug: #1451386
(cherry picked from commit c2a1fe786859314132a4fdfeb8ab3cb6e7ebdb46)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix 'AllocType' read failure in Huawei driver

The 'AllocType' have two values: Thin and Thick.
The following piece of code in the Huawei driver has
incorrect path and as a result the 'AllocType' is always
'None'. The correct values should be "Thin" or "Thick"
only.

'fstype = root.findtext('FILESYSTEM/AllocType')'

In code line 366: '"ALLOCTYPE": 1'
The "Thin" is set as the initial value. If the 'AllocType'
is always 'None', the 'AllocType' can not set as "Thick".

Change 'FILESYSTEM/AllocType' to 'Filesystem/AllocType' in
Huawei driver to avoid 'AllocType' can not be read out.

Change-Id: I63b77b8608b313729159d5732a5dae00cbe67034
Closes-Bug: #1451386
(cherry picked from commit c2a1fe786859314132a4fdfeb8ab3cb6e7ebdb46)

commit_message:
tests: make API signature test also check static function

The assertPublicAPISignatures method was not checking class
methods, nor any static functions, so it missed a few places
where a subclass was not following the parent class signature
correctly.

libvirt, xenapi & fake drivers had declared get_host_ip_addr() to
be static even though it was non-static in the parent class. libvirt
had declared 'uri' even though no such method existed in the parent.

Change-Id: Ic4d5aea6cd2485bac342678cee9b4d588bf14691

commit_message:
Don't run remove_ceph_mons when there are no controllers being deleted

When not deleting controllers we don't need to worry about
removing Ceph MONs.

Change-Id: I6b8ee02a1936cff26a55204b716b627d45defddd
Closes-bug: #1453408

commit_message:
Fix error in in-band disk erase using shred

in-band disk erase using shred fails with error "'module' object has no
attribute 'ProcessExecutionError'". This commit is to fix the issue.

Change-Id: Ia0c426074b2f0e9d534ed96a3e213933160edc61
Closes-Bug:#144799

commit_message:
Improve messaging on keystone connection issue

When connection could not be establish to keystone, it mostly
caused by misconfiguration. Updating the error message to make
it easier to troubleshooting.

Change-Id: I292838e57474f524f9b2910e6c22648d41006207
Closes-Bug: #1452955

commit_message:
Rename specs to match titles

Sphinx orders TOCTree entries by filename but lists the title. This
means that when the filename doesn't match the title, the list appears
to be unordered. That looks untidy and makes it a devil to find the spec
you're looking for.

Rename specs to match titles, using:

    for REL in specs/*/; do (
        cd $REL
        for TYPE in */; do (
            cd $TYPE
            for OLD in *.rst; do
                NEW=$(sed '/======/ {
                               N
                               s/.*\n\s*\(.*\S\)\s*$/\1/
                               s/ /-/g
                               s/[^a-zA-Z0-9.-]//g
                               q
                           }
                           d' $OLD).rst
                NEW=${NEW:l}  # ZSH-ism
                if [ "$OLD" != "$NEW" ]; then
                    git mv $OLD $NEW
                    echo "$TYPE/$OLD $NEW" >> ../redirects
                fi
            done
        ) done
    ) done

Change-Id: I8de98df64072fa3b7eddb7147905c97fc49eb5cd

commit_message:
Provide the memcache_pool fixes backport guide

This update to the ops guide describes how
to backport the memcache_pool fixes from the
6.0.x trunk branch to the existing
Fuel 6.0. It also adds the
memcached term in docs.

Closes-bug: #1441019
Closes-bug: #1433519

Change-Id: I5497bdd9fa3b8895e23e3602b95c3cd8a578475e
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit ac826c6dd952228e36f44776849c5172c79dd4cc)

commit_message:
Add support for haproxy_service_manage

We want to let the caller decide upon having the haproxy
service started and enabled or not on boot.

commit_message:
Increase timeout for test_create_images

Ostf tests for glances fails sometimes when we use VMware backend. It
doesn't affect production using but can confuse users.

It happens when VMware glance's backend has to restart auth session
and the test's timeout expires by timeout on some step. Obvious fix is
increasing timeouts.

I increase each timeout because session's restart may happens during
passage any step but don't increase estimation of duration time because
it may happens only one time and doesn't changes full time of working
test.

Change-Id: I6d50249443035c869329c47c73f286aedb272c1d
Partial-Bug: #1437228

commit_message:
Fix Rally application

Variables $repository & $version are defined in the class-level
scope and should be addressed as $.repository & $.version to
return actual value passed by the user.

Change-Id: Iff1bd16e7e02841a2b42962caaa285725b97b3d3
Closes-Bug: #1453586

commit_message:
Provide the memcache_pool fixes backport guide

This update to the ops guide describes how
to backport the memcache_pool fixes from the
6.0.x trunk branch to the existing
Fuel 6.0. It also adds the
memcached term in docs.

Closes-bug: #1441019
Closes-bug: #1433519

Change-Id: I5497bdd9fa3b8895e23e3602b95c3cd8a578475e
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix resource-signal for OS::Mistral::Workflow

Invoking signal resulted in ResourceFailure: TypeError: create() takes at most 3 arguments (4 given).
Updated test_signal_and_delete_with_executions to cover this bug.

Change-Id: I1b23f2b938977862266295974793d71dc9ff7570
Closes-Bug: #1453539

commit_message:
Correct Admin Instances actions to reference Admin ones

Currently "Console" and "View Log" actions are referencing the Project
version of these pages instead of the Admin version.

i.e. "Console" action redirects to Project > Instances > Detail page

Additionally, the Admin instance detail page is using the collection
of actions from the Project instance table.

This change corrects these references to redirect to the detail page
under the Admin panel group; updates the Admin detail page to use the
collection of actions from the Admin instance table.

Change-Id: I7043d8283c4f3a85e52b360a790aa3487b9a4ff7
Closes-Bug: 1421318

commit_message:
Expose in memory backend split staticmethod

Just like we expose join we should also expose
split to ensure that both of these operations
can easily performed by users of this backend.

This also refactors the internal usage to call
into that static method vs calling into the
posix path module specific one.

Change-Id: I496c730b86f0af6d4b637862a92482c0df6a63b3

[{'created': '2015-05-08 01:10:40.000000000', 'message': 'Avoid re-normalizing paths when following links

There is not any need to re-normalize internal paths
once the initial get() or __get_item__() have normalized
there path arguments so in _get_item() just tell the fetching
function to avoid re-normalizing the paths its provided.

This also works for link following since the target
placed in the fake inodes metadata is already normalized
when it is inserted.

Change-Id: If31d61b744f8df618c7db3afffc4a118cb17003a

This also works for link following since the target
placed in the fake inodes metadata is already normalized
when it is inserted.

Part of blueprint make-things-speedy

Change-Id: If31d61b744f8df618c7db3afffc4a118cb17003a
'}]
commit_message:
Avoid re-normalizing paths when following links

There is not any need to re-normalize internal paths
once the initial get() or __get_item__() have normalized
there path arguments so in _get_item() just tell the fetching
function to avoid re-normalizing the paths its provided.

This also works for link following since the target
placed in the fake inodes metadata is already normalized
when it is inserted.

Part of blueprint make-things-speedy

Change-Id: If31d61b744f8df618c7db3afffc4a118cb17003a

commit_message:
Avoid duplicating exception message

Now that we have exception chaining working nicely we
do not need to duplicate the original exceptions message
in followup exceptions (as the chain will by its very nature
have this same information/message); so let's stop duplicating
it.

Change-Id: I9b947c0d8c1df894de346835f92c12e8773349c4

commit_message:
Just let the future executors handle the max workers

Instead of providing and retaining a thread count in
the worker and action engine executors and checking it
and handling the none case, we can just let the future
types handle this already (which they already do). And
when displaying this information in the worker banner
use a new future executor attribute that is the maximum
number of workers that will be ever created.

Change-Id: I765c22936b53cdbb8a90195a764d4c67bcc3f34b

commit_message:
User Guides: Install CLIs is for both guides

These files are in the common directory and included by both guides, remove
the meta tag.

This also fixes the missing NEXT button on some pages.

Move two files from common to adminuser that are only shown in the admin guide.

Change-Id: I94c36239ca5f4431156cb339fe7e1c8d1d78aa7c
Closes-Bug: #1453896

commit_message:
Remove version string from the setup.cfg

PBR handles setting the version based on the git tags, so we don't need
to do this in the setup.cfg anymore.

Change-Id: Idf5871021fbcf6c40262df2936829d674cd13875

commit_message:
Update port 'binding:host_id' when VM is deleted

this patch fix that a VM booted with pre-existing port is deleted,
the port 'binding:host_id' can't be updated.

Change-Id: Ia94ecf8afa5b78c7c54be96b693513133804ad6b
Closes-Bug: #1441419

commit_message:
Add release notes for 0.5.0

This adds release notes for the following commits:

    $ git log --oneline --no-merges  0.4.0..HEAD
    b0798ac Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package
    751f9ae Fix RBD delete image on creation failure
    73bf032 Use is_valid_ipv6() from oslo.utils
    5c71f1d Properly instantiate Forbidden exception
    19fede3 Update README to work with release tools
    e8884d2 Remove ordereddict from requirements
    dc378a7 gridfs: add pymongo to test-requirements and update tests
    cddecb1 Add release notes for 0.1.10-0.3.0
    774d9ac Only warn on duplicate path on fs backend
    63fcfd5 Propagate BadStoreConfiguration to library user
    4d8a752 Update oslo libraries
    4fba478 Initialize vmware session during store creation

Change-Id: I25b165a9f04b155fe6471665ab346be76963316f

Does adding 'spec_set=True' to lines with 'autospec=True' have any benefit?

 You had commented here:
 https://review.openstack.org/#/c/174514/3/ironic/tests/drivers/irmc/test_management.py

 My understanding is that 'autospec=True' and 'spec=True' don't detect to assign a value to non existing attribute, but 'spec_set=True' can detect.

 Therefor I tried

 @mock.patch.object(ipmitool.IPMIManagement, 'set_boot_device', spec_set=True, autospec=True)

 set_boot_device_mock.aaa=1

 and I found out that it did NOT report AttributeError as I expected."}, {'account_id': 14760, 'date': '2015-04-29 16:06:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2015-04-30 01:25:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

John,

> Do we use autospec=True, spec_set=True even if it doesn't work as described in the URL?

I asked above question to you in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/174514/3/ironic/tests/drivers/irmc/test_management.py

But I didn't get your answer, so I judged that 'autospec=True,
spec_set=True' is correct coding because the manual says so.

----------

There is a more aggressive version of both spec and autospec that does prevent you setting non-existent attributes. This is useful if you want to ensure your code only sets valid attributes too, but obviously it prevents this particular scenario:

>>> with patch('__main__.Something', autospec=True, spec_set=True):
...   thing = Something()
...   thing.a = 33
...
Traceback (most recent call last):
 ...
AttributeError: Mock object has no attribute 'a'
----------

Best regards,

Naohiro"}, {'account_id': 13719, 'date': '2015-04-30 04:57:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

John,

I confirmed that 'autospec=True, spec_set=True' works as the manual specifies.

So please update your code-review, and let me know if you have further question.

best regards,
Naohiro

commit_message:
Improve strictness of iRMC test cases error checking

The 'spec_set' option of Mock object directs stricter checking than
'spec' option.
The commit 3084705ece7bd687835ff90dabe247a8d74d0d82 assigned
'spec_set' to the external functions of python-scciclient, but it
assigned 'spec' to the internal functions.
This patch makes strictness of the error checking consistent among
iRMC test cases.

Change-Id: I1ff907c60bd9096cc19a5c1e083c90261646165b

commit_message:
Make MagnumObject a subclass of Oslo VersionedObject

Slim down MagnumObject to accomodate the newest implementation from Oslo,
migrate all fields to their types defined in oslo_versionedobjects.fields.
This migrates almost all of the versioned objects code to Oslo, next patch
will implement the new registration scheme.

Related to blueprint versioned-objects

Change-Id: I75a77280042469ede05158683bc4f94e3b76abbd

commit_message:
Make docker volume config more resilient

* Since the volume is being hot plugged after instance boot, there
  is a chance cloud-init could get to the volume config script before
  the volume has been hot plugged. So, this adds a check that waits
  for the volume to be present.
* In order to make absolutely sure the disk by-id symlinks have been
  created by udev, we trigger udev before we check for the volume.

Change-Id: Ibeef639bd14bc85eeb65ba0d687f64ccf11f3c59
Closes-Bug: #1452853

commit_message:
Allow container name as identifier in API calls

This change adds support for using a Container's name instead of
it's UUID in Container API calls. If there is more than one
Container with the same name, an exception will be raised and the
user will need to provide a UUID instead.

Closes-Bug: #1452650

Change-Id: I058bde5f41016c91cf68a5b5c574d181a58e4836

commit_message:
Fixes cinder races

Cinder is failing after upgrade to Juno. This is because of the
following race conditions:

  - Cinder takes time to update the current status of the services.
  - Cinder sometimes gets stuck at creating block device.
  - While creating block device, deleting that device is not allowed.
    This creates error and stops the script from running.

Fixes include some helper functions which adds to the robustness of
cinder test cases.

Co-Authored-By: Roger Luethi <rl@patchworkscience.org>
Change-Id: I3254438fdac0bd4a7f927f0f203c51ab6e45b9c0

commit_message:
Simplify RST building

Use a script to build and copy RST guides around instead of duplicating
the same lines every time.

Use script in build-user-guides.sh for now. A follow-up patch shall
change further places.

This script will eventually be moved over to openstack-doc-tools, let's
first evolve it here and check that we cover all use cases.

Change-Id: I753e742bf77b2d6f5acf2f909d62af3dd422832a

commit_message:
Remove duplicate requirements from test-requirements.txt

These get installed via requirements.txt. This is in preparation
for adding the global requirements test job to our pipeline, which
would fail if it found duplicates like this.

Change-Id: I62abe22bd04702e491d7c2f09e5c89408fccf399

commit_message:
Remove support for loading auth plugin by class

Keystone used to support setting the [auth] methods config option
to a fully-qualified class. This has been deprecated since the
Juno release.

Setting the [auth] methods config option to a fully-qualified class
name will no longer work.

bp stevedore

Change-Id: I4adbc7d271fde264bc569ed51656d3c09737b98b

commit_message:
update akanda acls to support branching

akanda project acls were missing
the create akanda-release.
This will allow akanda project to
create branches through gerrit.

Closes-Bug: #1453914
Partially Implements: blueprint ci-updates

Change-Id: I5ea2bc65b5a0f2cc495f6c22efacd0e5753e96ec

[{'created': '2015-05-08 22:04:03.000000000', 'message': 'qemu image compatibility fixes

QEMU images created with disk-image-create default to compat=1.1, which
does not work with some public cloud providers (e.g. HP Public Cloud).
Adding a flag to select QEMU Image options and defaulting to
compat=0.10, which works for all QEMU versions > 0.10

Change-Id: I1e5f97b259ca47c432715604a661efc2e11eafce
Closes-Bug: 1453278
'}]
commit_message:
qemu image compatibility fixes

QEMU images created with disk-image-create default to compat=1.1, which
does not work with some public cloud providers (e.g. HP Public Cloud).
Adding a flag to select QEMU Image options and defaulting to
compat=0.10, which works for all QEMU versions > 0.10

Change-Id: I1e5f97b259ca47c432715604a661efc2e11eafce
Closes-Bug: 1453278

commit_message:
Make test_version_string_with_package_is_good work with pbr 0.11

nova.version uses the version_string() API not version. Fix the test to
reflect that and make it work with pbr 0.11

Closes-Bug: #1450682

commit_message:
Allow setting router's external ip(s)

This change allows to set external_fixed_ips in router-gateway-set
command using --fixed-ip option:

  neutron router-gateway-set $router $extnet\
      --fixed-ip ip_address=10.0.0.4
  neutron router-gateway-set $router $extnet\
      --fixed-ip subnet_id=extsubnet

Change-Id: Ifa37aee0bbf8e2ee1eb37020924f13af73ad35cc
Related: blueprint specify-router-ext-ip

commit_message:
Delete swarm bay also delete related containers

Currently, when we delete a swarm bay, we didn't delete related
container and these containers are useless.

This patch delete the related containers when delete a swarm bay.

Change-Id: I8fbbba38de4db8a87b2894751075bddee6e129ad
Closes-Bug: #1452167
(cherry picked from commit a6e04f61fe15d38436355a8e9c84ed9fb81d5a8b)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-31 23:57:03.000000000', 'message': 'Improve IPA client library

The Ironic Python Agent client library was limited and made supporting
more commands difficult (such as decommission). This adds a class to
represent the results from the commands, which should make development
a bit less error prone. Also, added improved error handling of connections
to the client and parsing of results.

commit_message:
Improve IPA client library

The Ironic Python Agent client library was limited and made supporting
more commands difficult (such as zap()). This adds a class to
represent the results from the commands, which should make development
a bit less error prone. Added improved error handling of connections
to the client and parsing of results. Fixed the agent getting queried
multiple times when prepare_image completes.

Co-Authored-By: Kyle Stevenson <kyle@kylestevenson.me>
Closes-Bug: 1368906

This changes the status code when the database is down from 400 to 500 -- which is correct. It is a server-side error. I would support refactoring that fix out into a separate (small) patch.

I'm -1'ing this patch because it does not fix the issue at the correct tier. It should instead be fixed at the db.api layer.

Also, it does not address several types of DB errors, such as what happens when a table is missing or the table definition is wrong. Eg, with this patch, I still get the following details exposed by the client, along with the full SQL query which I haven't pasted here.

  (ProgrammingError) (1146, "Table 'ironic.ports' doesn't exist")

  (OperationalError) (1054, "Unknown column 'ports.address' in 'field list'")'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Sorry about the conflicting inputs there -- I realize that I wasn't very clear. Here are my thoughts on the issue:


* SQL traces should -never- be sent in an HTTP response. Catching only a specific list of error codes coming from MySQL is not the best way to handle this when we support multiple back-ends (we test with sqlite, mysql, and postgres...)
* It can be helpful to log a SQL trace, when the error was SQL-related, if debugging is enabled... but usually, just logging the database error is sufficient. If it's an unexpected db exception, logging the python stack trace will be helpful, too.
* Logging the real database error (rather than the IronicDBError string) will be helpful to operators.
* Obfuscated database errors should be presented to users, not operators. This is why I meant it should not be done at the db.api tier.

Also, in re-reading the history here, I also spotted a few other things:

* explicitly logging the exception in the API tier is not necessary (we just removed this in another patch)
* exception messages need to be i18n'd. Eg, message = _("Message Body")


HTH,
Devananda'}, {'account_id': 10380, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 10380, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Restored'}, {'account_id': 10380, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

recheck no bug'}, {'account_id': 10380, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

The first patch did fix it at the DB API layer, but you suggested moving it to the controller layer, since this would mask exceptions on conductor calls. I agree the DB API is the appropriate layer. Maybe I can wrap DB errors in the IronicDBError class, giving them appropriate error messages, and logging the full, unmodified exception. That way an operator can still see the appropiate errors, and DB details aren't leaked to the REST API. 

Thanks for the notes on the other errors not caught. I'll see what I can do there."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Fix leaking DB details to API on error

Most of the DB exceptions contain DB details which aren't caught by the
traceback hook. The cleanest way to ensure the proper error codes and
messages are being sent is to catch the DBErrors and wrap them as
IronicExceptions. This patch will show the DB details if debug is enabled,
but hides them behind a generic message if debug is False.

The patch tries to cover every possible case by wrapping all public methods
in sqlalchemy.api.Connection and reraising IronicDBError for all
unexpected database exceptions.

Closes-Bug: #1277555
Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Tantsur <dtantsur@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Icfd3bea9bda7e70a46ca221632a0258e7378b578

commit_message:
Handles modules that moved in Python3

Many modules moved in Python3 as the namespace was cleaned up. This uses
six.move so that we don't need to have different imports for different
verisons of Python.

bp python3
Change-Id: Ic93f16a5fe995bfaf7054172875f156b55a3770a

commit_message:
Handles Python3 builtin changes

Some of the builtins (like map) have changed in Python3 in a way that
can lead to broken Python2 code.

bp python3

Uhm, I'm not so sure about the approach. This now requires developers to have a specific setup (or specific users and projects) to test barbican. Probably I'm doing it wrong but I share the Barbican dev environment with my keystone dev environment.

I would prefer if instead of setting up those users and projects in the devstack script (or keystone sample data script also); the users and projects would be set up in the test case's setUpClass method. You could even share that method with all the other test cases that will need them. https://docs.python.org/2/library/unittest.html#unittest.TestCase.setUpClass

Then in the tearDownClass method you could delete them, thus keeping the dev environment clean."}, {'account_id': 7136, 'date': '2015-04-27 00:07:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 11561, 'date': '2015-04-27 00:23:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Workflow-1

I like @Juan's suggestion.  Please don't merge this until I have a chance to try that out."}, {'account_id': 7136, 'date': '2015-04-27 00:38:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 10873, 'date': '2015-04-28 13:11:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2

Having discussed with Dave over IRC it was concluded that the approach I suggested is not optimal, and the initial approach is better due to the predictability and stability that it implies. Creating users and projects on the fly only for the tests could easily lead to pollution of the dev environment. So if someone runs that on their machines it could be annoying.'}, {'account_id': 11561, 'date': '2015-04-28 13:15:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Workflow'}, {'account_id': 11561, 'date': '2015-04-28 13:22:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

I get a few errors when running keystone_data.sh on a clean Keystone installation (using John Vrbanac's Simple Dockerized Keystone: https://registry.hub.docker.com/u/jmvrbanac/simple-keystone/)

usage: keystone user-create --name <user-name> [--tenant <tenant>]
                            [--pass [<pass>]] [--email <email>]
                            [--enabled <true|false>]
keystone user-create: error: argument --tenant_id: expected one argument
usage: keystone user-role-add --user <user> --role <role> [--tenant <tenant>]
keystone user-role-add: error: argument --tenant_id: expected one argument

It looks like these errors are fixed by changing SERVICE_TENANT and MEMBER_ROLE like so:

SERVICE_TENANT=$(get_id keystone tenant-create --name="service")
MEMBER_ROLE=$(keystone role-list | awk "/ _member_ / { print \$2 }")

Initially all functional tests were failing after running keystone_data.sh, but after making the above changes, they are all passing now.'}, {'account_id': 11561, 'date': '2015-04-30 00:24:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Add Multi-user support for Functional Tests

This commit adds the infrastructure for multi user testing.  It also adds
a small set of test cases that exercises RBAC policy for secret and
container reads.

Six users with four roles and two projects are added.
   In Project A: admin_a, creator_a, observer_a, auditor_a
   In Project B: admin_b, observer_b

Get Secrets and Get Containers are tested for each user.

Implements: blueprint add-run-as-for-functional-tests
Relates-to: blueprint multi-user-functional-tests

Change-Id: I65c820440c014301cfce90d360440d3e12e7ffba

commit_message:
Add worker config support

Allow the various workers to be configured as attributes.
The engine one is based upon cpu, so default is nil just like
in Compute.  The others default to zero, so used that.

Change-Id: Id7382ceeb4daeb6136e4b10546eed26901fbc3eb
Closes-Bug: #1452734

commit_message:
Ignore new N324 style requirement

There is a lot of code the violates this new requirement, and
thus is currently causing all neutron-lbaas CRs to be held up.

I vote that we ignore the requirement for the time being. Who agrees?

Change-Id: Ie86c95227f51f95f222434a8d5e6f9252ae4b33f

commit_message:
Update template paths for environment-mapped TemplateResources

When updating a template resource, we weren't taking into account the
possibility that the new environment could be mapping the resource to a
different template path. This change ensures we recalculate the template
name from the new environment before reloading the template during an
update.

Co-Authored-By: Angus Salkeld <asalkeld@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I5f84f6fd60925d3dba0b8e8dec867657c8c5c9ef
Closes-Bug: #1452534
(cherry picked from commits 686f317ccae280bd8b536379e89ba743746ae159 and
                            8c37b56acef04178e07591eecde27a50f7ef5ac9)

Change-Id: I25320897e10cfd181bb361861a9481afac1af378

commit_message:
networking-ovn: disable n-novnc

Disable n-novnc in the networking-ovn tempest job.  It's not needed
and causes devstack to try to clone the noVNC git repo.  devstack is
set to fail on any git_clone call, so this makes the job fail.

Change-Id: I25320897e10cfd181bb361861a9481afac1af378

commit_message:
Session usage improved in sqlalchemy api

The oslo_db doc recommends to use session.add instead of .save() on models.
The job_execution_update fixed to actually save the change.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-08 17:04:31.000000000', 'message': "Use an actual existing nova scheduler in README.md

The Multi-Node Setup guide in README.md

    https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/tree/master#multi-node-setup

guides users to use

    SCHEDULER=nova.scheduler.simple.SimpleScheduler

where the SimpleScheduler doesn't actually exist in nova. Even
though this is just an example, it is misleading enough for a
beginner to put SimpleScheduler into local.conf. The resulting
error message where n-sch fails to start

    ImportError: No module named simple

Isn't intuitive enough and may takes the beginner long time to
locate what's wrong.

This patch replaces SimpleScheduler with a real existing
FilterScheduler in nova.

Change-Id: I14a2a5c0604ce08a498accfc3a795c1c9aa3e642
Closes-bug: #1453186
"}]
commit_message:
Use an actual existing nova scheduler in README.md

The Multi-Node Setup guide in README.md

    https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/tree/master#multi-node-setup

guides users to use

    SCHEDULER=nova.scheduler.simple.SimpleScheduler

where the SimpleScheduler doesn't actually exist in nova. Even
though this is just an example, it is misleading enough for a
beginner to put SimpleScheduler into local.conf. The resulting
error message where n-sch fails to start

    ImportError: No module named simple

Isn't intuitive enough and may takes the beginner long time to
locate what's wrong.

This patch replaces SimpleScheduler with a real existing
FilterScheduler in nova.

Change-Id: I14a2a5c0604ce08a498accfc3a795c1c9aa3e642
Closes-bug: #1453186

commit_message:
Make hook type optional for hook-clear

We can derive the correct hook type (and do some sanity assertions,
as in hook-poll) via the stack status, so it's slightly easier,
particularly for scripts, if you don't need to explicitly specify
the hook type.

The old options are retained for compatibility, and I guess they
will make the call slightly more efficient.

Change-Id: I622f13e10d17e31ea2a6a2d7647c3e6ef3b085bf

Still needs tests, and I'm going to refactor so the common list mangling code goes in event_utils, as I know Jan is looking to use this from a python rather than shell interface.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-04-29 16:25:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

we have available now in kilo Heat.

commit_message:
Add hook-poll function to check if a stack has pending hooks

Currently using the breakpoints/hooks functionality on large trees of
stacks is a bit inconvenient, because you may set hooks in nested stacks
so the events aren't easily visible via the top-level event interfaces.

This has been addressed via the new --nested-depth option to event-list,
but it's still hard to determine (programatically e.g from a script) if
there's pending hook which requires clearing.

So this patch introduces an initial implementation of a specialized
event-list function "hook-poll", which filters the events and displays
only those events which have pending hooks (e.g those which have yet
to be signalled to clear them).

I expect the efficiency of the implementation can be much improved in the
future if we add a propert nested_depth argument to the heat events API,
and/or add a hook API which enables easier introspection of hook status.
The CLI interface should be reasonable in the event such rework happens,
but the current (slow) implementation will work with the API interfaces
we have available now in kilo Heat.

Change-Id: I71b19202ab29f44e5c09b4ee04be4aeaea038c28

commit_message:
cfg: support interpolation of config option from other groups

This patch adds support for config variable interpolation with values
coming form… other groups than the current/default one!

Change-Id: Iddd21aa2da71fe332868049d4b94b75b562b61cd

commit_message:
rabbit: fix exception path in queue redeclaration

This removes a TODO, that was not possible before the consumer code
refactoring.

Now, we can just catch the right exception instead of catching
everything and pray.

Change-Id: Id6203d79d4b2f027e5c6cd952c99fcd0967ecb3c

commit_message:
Switch pip-missing-reqs for pip-check-reqs

pip-missing-reqs was renamed to pip-check-reqs, additionally,
we import from setuptools, so we should include it in our
requirements.txt

Change-Id: Ic963aa8056196d7e99c446f3e1156f05195aab62

commit_message:
rabbit: fix consumers declaration

When a consumer is declared after we have started to consume
amqp, its queue is never consumed.

This fixes that.

Closes bug: #1450342

Change-Id: I9f2e7d83283504dfe762ac88384efde0f7b52d47

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-30 16:28:17.000000000', 'message': "rabbit: remove unused consumer interfaces

The consumer code is over engineered, it allows to override
everything, but the override is always done with functools.partial.

None of the child Class have the same signature, sometimes
the constructor use the parameter name as the parent class but for
a different purpose, that makes the code hard to read.

It's was never clear which options is passed to the queue and the
exchange at this end to kombu.

This changes removes all of that stuffs, and only use the kombu
terminology for consumer parameters.

Alse we don't hardcode anymore the tag and the channel in the consumer
class, to allow to change them without recreating a consumer object
in the futur.

Change-Id: Ie341f0c973adbda9a342cb836867345aa42652d1
"}, {'created': '2015-04-30 16:37:01.000000000', 'message': "rabbit: remove unused consumer interfaces

The consumer code is over engineered, it allows to override
everything, but the override is always done with functools.partial.

None of the child Class have the same signature, sometimes
the constructor use the parameter name as the parent class but for
a different purpose, that makes the code hard to read.

It's was never clear which options is passed to the queue and the
exchange at this end to kombu.

This changes removes all of that stuffs, and only use the kombu
terminology for consumer parameters.

commit_message:
rabbit: remove unused consumer interfaces

The consumer code is over engineered, it allows to override
everything, but the override is always done with functools.partial.

None of the child Class have the same signature, sometimes
the constructor use the parameter name as the parent class but for
a different purpose, that makes the code hard to read.

It's was never clear which options is passed to the queue and the
exchange at this end to kombu.

This changes removes all of that stuffs, and only use the kombu
terminology for consumer parameters.

Alse we don't hardcode anymore the tag and the channel in the consumer
class, to allow to change them without recreating a consumer object
in the futur.

Change-Id: Ie341f0c973adbda9a342cb836867345aa42652d1

commit_message:
Adds pypi-jobs to cloudbase-init

Pushing a version through gerrit should also publish
the version to pypi.

Pypi project: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/cloudbase-init/
openstackci is added as admin user.

commit_message:
Put in Sahara repo actual scenario files

Now scenario files placed in Sahara repo aren't equal to scenario files
which actually is using in Sahara CI.

Also we want to use scenario files from Sahara repo, instead
Sahara CI repo, so we need to update this files.

Closes-bug: #1447316

Change-Id: Id6adb8f89934ffe4ceb85cf7c12359dca8eff09e

commit_message:
Improve compatible with python3

Changes:
* use six.iteritems instead dict.iteritems
* use urllib in CDH API client
* filtering directories in HDP versionhandler because py3 creates
  __pycache__ directory

Unit tests result:

Ran: 750 tests in 13.4569 sec.
 - Passed: 669
 - Skipped: 5
 - Expected Fail: 0
 - Unexpected Success: 0
 - Failed: 76

commit_message:
Use [] where a value is required

The use of .get() implies that having no value, or None is ok,
but in the case that's fixed here, a value of None would result
in an error, so [] is correct to use here.

Change-Id: I47113121c10c2d0682daf40eb616b379e2d212e8

commit_message:
De-duplicate auth methods

The [auth] methods config option allowed specifying the same plugin
multiple times, but it would just fail anyway since duplicates
aren't allowed. Rather than fail, de-duplicate the [auth] methods
values.

bp stevedore

Change-Id: I14e27e600efa97887f7b36c240a1063565c94f2a

commit_message:
Use the 'base' element implicitly everywhere

Now that the 'centos' element is used for CentOS images, there is no
more need to exclude the 'base' element; thus, the usage of -n for
disk-image-create can be removed.  Also, 'base' makes sure the distro is
up-to-date, so the usage of 'updater' can be removed too.

As side change, since 'base' is implicit unless -n is passed, remove its
usage, also removing the -n usage with it.

Change-Id: I5b829264ac1b3d51a7e3c5fa9b60676c5dcc2e74

commit_message:
Remove workaround for old eventlet version

Swift now requires eventlet >= 0.16.1, so we can get rid of this
workaround for a bug in eventlet 0.9.16.

Change-Id: I4a1200b9bd9266896a704a840fda0d1b720bc86d

That rewrite should address the structural problems you mention; it doesn't now but I totally agree with your assessment about the way initialize_app() is structured, I'm afraid fixing that may include making some basic changes to cliff too.

Do you have a suggestion about where to put functional (or maybe integration?) tests that still do not need an operational could to run? commit_message:
Add os-client-config cli tests

Add tests for --os-cloud handling and precedence between CLI,

commit_message:
Add support for settings wsgi MAX_HEADER_LINE

Changes default from 8192 to 16384 and adds a configuration option.

Change-Id: Ia6dc883c60e32e54124fc4d9e5853021c861c284
Closes-Bug: 1453591

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: If5e8257085b5fd0a26a34705505fc0077adbabb2

[{'created': '2015-05-11 07:07:22.000000000', 'message': 'Libvirt: Use tpool to invoke guestfs api

In inspect_capabilities() of nova/virt/disk/vfs/guestfs.py, guestfs api, which
is C-extension, will hang nova-compute process when it is invoked. This problem
will result in message queue timeout error and instance booting failure. Need
to use tpool to invoke guestfs api, in order to make nova-compute switch to

Closes-Bug: 1453666
'}]
commit_message:
Libvirt: Use tpool to invoke guestfs api

In inspect_capabilities() of nova/virt/disk/vfs/guestfs.py, guestfs api, which
is C-extension, will hang nova-compute process when it is invoked. This problem
will result in message queue timeout error and instance booting failure. Need
to use tpool to invoke guestfs api, in order to make nova-compute switch to
other green threads before guestfs api returns.

Change-Id: I24187ba01965fb886351b78eee605bc052a94e21
Closes-Bug: 1453666

commit_message:
Make a demo for Magnum

Make a Magnum demonstration that creates a baymodel and bay.  Just
run demos/magnum/launch to make it work.  This depends on Neutron.

Borrow the v1beta3 redis example from the examples repository in
Kubernetes.
Change-Id: I448a5890bfe0c1675914ae7dbd02fad03f4b1eeb

commit_message:
install-guides: suse: Update nova-compute section

Adds missing dependency 'libvirt' to installation command. For suse
related packages, libvirt is not installed by default.

Change-Id: I685cad41cf61f80c7d98b02ebe67414fe04c83fa

commit_message:
Address comments on virtual media device label commit

This commit address last comments on
I5e8a706989bad13051eb47db0b1e762e6c672318. It adds
the date for a comment was added and removes redundant
wait period for initialization.

Change-Id: Idff38835969c094175f68be78c407ae975473b57

commit_message:
ironic/tests/drivers: Add autospec=True and spec_set=

Add autospec=True and spec_set= to mocks.

Attempt to add in following priority order:
1. autospec=True
2. spec_set= some specification
3. spec= some specification
4. autospec=False to indicate to future developers that an attempt had
   been previously made.

If unable to set 'autospec=True' on @classmethod functions or possibly
other functions, use spec_set=types.FunctionType or
spec=types.FunctionType

Change mock.Mock() to mock.MagicMock()

Also did some minor cleanup in places.

Change-Id: I804a501a361dbef4dbceafa5d77b24ef015267bf

commit_message:
How To: Adjust Placement Groups for new Ceph Nodes

Currently fuel only calculates pg_num and pgp_num for ceph pools as part
of the initial deployment. When additional nodes are added to an
environment it may be necessary to update these values for the ceph
deployment for optimal performance. This document explains how to do
this manually until this functionality can be rolled into the fuel
deployment process.

Change-Id: I7ed502a1665ea314ab3dd4f868eca865fe550961
Partial-Bug: 1383931

commit_message:
HEAD does not imply HTTP 204

Keystone recently revised it's HEAD behavior to correctly reflect the
HTTP spec's description, which suggests that the status code provided in
response to a HEAD request should be exactly that which would have been
returned if the same resource had been retrieved with a GET.

Change-Id: I4c8ea4e49f32608a42b62a236985a80eb6b555d3

End users may not realize these files are autogenerated
and may be surprised if they make changes to the

Change-Id: I526c228463bd10de2cf3724aa4159b63a9aeff80

commit_message:
Mark ENI files as autogenerated

End users may not realize these files are autogenerated
and may be surprised if they make changes to the
/etc/sysconfig/network-scripts files which are then
overwritten on reboot.

Change-Id: I526c228463bd10de2cf3724aa4159b63a9aeff80

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Allow to install OVS from source in Ubuntu 14.04

According to possibility to deploy Openstack Juno on
Ubuntu 14.04 will be great to have way to install OVS
from source. In current situation it's impossible to
mix Ubuntu 14.04 and use_source_version=True.

Change-Id: I8e65defd01e71288a4c279aa411e295e74ef75c9

The actual attribute returned in object references of the /protocols API
is 'id', as in all other keystone APIs that return objects. The
implementation of new_ref() here doesn't actually include an 'id'
reference though, and goes out of it's way to test the wrong thing. This
patch fix that, eliminates the workarounds, and does a touch of

commit_message:
Use 'id' instead of 'protocol_id' in federation protocol tests

The actual attribute returned in object references of the /protocols API
is 'id', as in all other keystone APIs that return objects. The
implementation of new_ref() here doesn't actually include an 'id'
reference though, and goes out of it's way to test the wrong thing. This
patch fix that, eliminates the workarounds, and does a touch of
refactoring to bring these tests in line with tests of other client
managers.

Change-Id: I9a272b3ef91934e780106d89b5091b4bfb87ad29
Closes-Bug: 1453847

add a check for that on horizon.

commit_message:
Include OVSDB server states in agent heart-beats

The patch set makes the Monitoring L2gw agent include
the OVSDB server states in its heart beats. This way,
the administrator can know the connection states of the
OVSDB servers. These states will also help us in retrying
failures in future patch sets.

Change-Id: I3adb20ef2b0434ed78dc43b553eb5f6922bb0bc6

commit_message:
Add ability to disable stunnel

This change adds the ability to "turn off" the stunnel configuration for
the openstack services by unsetting the service configurations when
stunnel.connect_host is not set.

Change-Id: I469b1f02285dfa235d19cd6a7343c929d50dd31b

commit_message:
Fix and enhance "Exercising the Services Locally" docs

Fix and enhance some parts of the "Exercising the Services Locally"
documentation. Also, this patch is updating the RHEL instructions to
support RHEL7 (not RHEL6).

commit_message:
Point DIB builds at the devstack checkout of akanda-appliance

This allows the built appliance image to contain the code that was
checked out by devstack, allowing people (or bots) to test
code that has not landed in the akanda-appliance repo.

Change-Id: I25c0278b6f3879a45bf52888b83eeb20d9571807

commit_message:
Move Horizon to / and make it work in the first place.

Having the dasboard in /dashboard doesn't feel right, especially
since there is no automatic redirect when people browse to the ip or
hostname. Which would be a natural first try. Moving to / now to make
the process behave in a simpler fashion.

Because of a packaging error the js/css wouldn't load properly, next
to that there is an issue with a supposed missing 'manage.py
compress' run. This is handled through Kolla now as well (for the
time being).
There is another supposed bug in packaging that makes webfont.ttf
return a 404. This is because of a missing alias for /static stuff,
and with moving the whole thing to / this gets adressed as well.

Change-Id: I64cd7c9effad6cf9ec7c6a41f34e1184640c8adc

commit_message:
Add a Lotto token provider

Instead of boring UUIDs, let OpenStack open the door to untold riches by
generating lottery numbers for tokens. The current implementation uses
the Powerball algorithm, which is a large multi-state US lottery game.
The odds of a repeat token are about the same as the odds of winning the
jackpot, 1 in 175,223,510.

doc-impact

Change-Id: I52cf2b56b6629c7819454de1e52116c4c6838440

commit_message:
Fix snakeoil_ca plugin

This fixes creation of certificates using the snakeoil_ca plugin, like
passing the configuration properly and encoding resulting data, and adds
support for stored-key requests.

Closes-Bug: #1451456
Change-Id: Ida24a192595429829e870838a487a9c100691b4c

commit_message:
Increase timeout to 10 min for net_probe actions

For 200 nodes get_probing_info action may take more than 5 minutes
to finish. To fix it net_checker requires some refactoring.
For now increasing time should be enough.

Change-Id: Ia3451392b1bfca9d9812c6a397626cdc295fefde
Closes-bug: #1378500

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by

package, replacing it with the new package names.

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages
