commit_message:
Change data sent from netchecher to nailgun

There are two changes here:
- remove from the hash data sent by node to itself
- send to nailgun only non empty data

In https://review.openstack.org/#/c/178133/3 data sent to net checker changed.
Before it expected all tags to be recived on all nodes. Now tags for public network
are only recived on controllers.

Related-bug: #1397369

Change-Id: I8389dc4a05a6be6560135747020e74889fe8e18c

commit_message:
Spec for Hyper-V generation 2 VMs

This blueprint proposes the introduction of Hyper-V generation 2 VMs
support in the Nova Hyper-V compute driver.

Note: This blueprint was already approved (as a trivial blueprint)
and merged in Kilo. It is resubmitted as of ML thread:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/063178.html

Co-Authored-By: Claudiu Belu <cbelu@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Implements: blueprint hyper-v-generation-2-vms

Change-Id: I1b0f145bbb17df8cd6578ebd7ce0588acab9bb50

commit_message:
Update service manifest parsing according to v1beta3

Now that Kubernetes 0.15.0 release is supported and it has
v1beta3, the manifest structure has changed from v1beta1 to
v1beta3. This change implements the v1beta3 manifest parsing
logic for service resource of Kubernetes.

Change-Id: I1200473f91118eaa48b1cec386f30cf8a50708b5
Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient
(cherry picked from commit 08a27f1c0f8423d630ccf8bfb760a7aee1785457)

[{'created': '2015-04-30 22:56:01.000000000', 'message': "Remove version string from the setup.cfg

PBR handles setting the version based on the git tags, so we don't need
to do this in the setup.cfg anymore.

Change-Id: I3c12f54682b58c9eea5b40fa2c34979775c0b827
"}]
commit_message:
Remove version string from the setup.cfg

PBR handles setting the version based on the git tags, so we don't need
to do this in the setup.cfg anymore.

Change-Id: I3c12f54682b58c9eea5b40fa2c34979775c0b827

commit_message:
Using django-nose>=1.2 needed by murano-dashboard

After I packaged Murano, I discovered that its unit tests are
only working with Django-nose >= 1.2. I already wired this
into the build-dependency of the package, but the fact is,
its test-requirements.txt should reflect the reality.

I've checked, and Ubuntu Trusy already has django-nose 1.2.
As for Debian (which I manage), it's not a problem either.
My only concern would be RedHat and Gentoo, for which I
don't know how to check. Please guys, voice your opinion.

Change-Id: I1467842dede515a2dbc98986bf3d3df5f0d13cd3

Fix typo in log messages and comments

Fixed following typos in log messages and comment strings

accesible -> accessible
Extacts -> Extracts
intitiators -> initiators
swith -> switch
unavailble -> unavailable

So I don't understand why this is needed at all.

If the dir doesn't exist, our code that generates the password file will throw an error, right?
If the dir is out of space, likewise, and
If the dir can't be written to by our user also.

So AFAICT this patch is adding a bunch of code we need to maintain, in order to change where the errors are signalled.

But these aren't the only ways that generating a password file might fail, so I don't understand why these particular failure modes deserve special handling, vs reporting of ipmitool failures in general.

In python generally one should catch exceptions rather than doing pre-checks, in particular when dealing with external resources where pre-checks are subject to race conditions."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-05 05:02:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

Also, the check code is duplicated 4 times, and would be better done in a single private method.

commit_message:
Check temp dir is usable for ipmitool driver

This patch adds directory check functions to common/utils.py.
It adds a call to the new check functions in ipmitool init.
So we can test the temp directory, upon startup to ensure that
the directory is usable.

These pre-flight checks do not change the need for valid
and accurate error handling, They are to quickly inform
an operator that there is a configuration error that will
prevent the driver from performing as expected.

Also adds a missing unit test for the ipmitool drivers power
validate function "test_power_validate".

Change-Id: Iefc75203ccde1d25fd91c9cb815d871b068255a2
Partial-Bug: #1428722

commit_message:
[Launch Instance Fix] Add Details Step Unit Tests

This patch adds unit tests for the details step.  These tests are focused
around the controller and its related components (no selenium tests or view
tests).

Change-Id: Ie37a17e44b235072b43e3549ad04a57cadec9c05
Partial-Bug: 1435869

commit_message:
nova: remove allow_migrate_to_same_host config usage

Nova commit 9b224641295af3763d011816d6399565ac7b98de removed the option
in Liberty so we can remove it's usage in devstack.

Related-Bug: #1364851

Change-Id: If051f43fb75d57c118db4e8e97895ff06fbb54e2

commit_message:
Refactor common event code into event_utils module

The recently added event-mangling code for event-list --nested-depth
will also be needed for hook-poll functionality, so refactor to move
the code and tests into seperate files.

Change-Id: I6d349e1e2056f6a6ad5b683d8d40072b61dbf35c

commit_message:
Fix the container delete uuid issue

Query db first to make sure container exist or not, and then
call remote api for container

Closes-Bug: #1453709
Change-Id: Ib74120a5d7f560e878b7dd26183173679c6cc75c

It suggests that name servers are IP addresses only (which is sane). I don't think whether there is any reasonable meaning behind allowing nameservers to be passed as host names. commit_message:
Kill hostname validation for subnet:dns_nameservers

DNS servers that are hostnames seem like a bad idea. They are also not
supported by base_db_plugin_v2 [1] anyway, so there is no big reason to
pass them thru API validation only to receive InvalidInput later inside
plugin code.

[1]: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/neutron/tree/neutron/db/db_base_plugin_v2.py#n1049

Change-Id: I2db00fe266fe0748d0e6327fbad22fa16b751da8
Related-Bug: #1396932

commit_message:
rabbit: Remove unused stuffs from publisher

The publisher code is over engineered, it allows to override
everything, but this is never used.

None of the child Class have the same signature, sometimes
the constructor use the parameter name as the parent class but for
a different purpose, that make the code hard to read.

It's was never clear which options is passed to the queue and the
exchange at this end to kombu.

This changes removes all of that stuffs, and only use the kombu
terminology for publisher parameters.

Change-Id: I3cebf3ed1647a3121dcf33e2160cf315486f5204

[{'created': '2015-05-07 21:28:01.000000000', 'message': 'Remove support for redis < 2.6.0

To enable lua (and eval) usage to be accessible we
need to bump the min version to 2.6 (which should be
available on all distros that openstack is running
on).

This does that version bump and removes the code that
was handling and checking older versions (and the
differences/lack of APIs).

commit_message:
Remove support for redis < 2.6.0

To enable lua (and eval) usage to be accessible we
need to bump the min version to 2.6 (which should be
available on all distros that openstack is running
on).

This does that version bump and removes the code that
was handling and checking older versions (and the
differences/lack of APIs).

Change-Id: Ie8cd99d55e1907bb545b6692834b03871d9c1f83

commit_message:
Add spec for 'Failover to alternative iSCSI portals on login failure'

When the main iSCSI portal is unreachable by network failure etc.,
volume attach/detach will fail even though the other portal addresses
is reachable. To enable nova-compute to fail-over to alternative portal
addresses, cinder will tell the alternative portal addresses to nova.
When alternative portal addresses are provided, nova should handle them.

Change-Id: Id851170be7a84865d66a7ce1075b26546df8bca9
blueprint: iscsi-alternative-portal

commit_message:
Router is not unscheduled when the last port is deleted

When checking for ports that are still in use on a DVR router,
the L3 agent scheduler makes the assumption that a port's
network must be owned by the same tenant. This isn't always
true as the admin could have created a shared network that
other tenants may use. The result of this assumption is that
the router associated with the shared network may not be
unscheduled from a VM host when the last VM (created by a
non-admin tenant) using the shared network is deleted from
the compute node.

The owner of a VM may not own all the ports of a shared
network.  Other tenants may have VMs using the same shared
network running on the same compute node. Also the VM owner
may not own the router ports. In order to check whether a
router can be unscheduled from a node has to be run with
admin context so all the ports associated with router are
returned from database queries.

This patch fixes this problem by using the admin context to
make the queries needed for the DVR scheduler to make the
correct unschedule decision.

(cherry picked from commit edbade486102a219810137d1c6b916e87475d477)

Conflicts:
    neutron/db/l3_dvrscheduler_db.py

Closes-bug: #1424096
Change-Id: I45477713d7ce16f2451fa6fbe04c610388b06867

recommendation to use mod_wsgi more strongly than has been made in

"}]
commit_message:
Improve ceilometer-api install documentation

This updates the mod_wsgi configuration and installation information
to be more in line with current usage. It also makes the
recommendation to use mod_wsgi more strongly than has been made in
the past. In general we don't want people to be running
ceilometer-api at all, but it is good for them to have the option.

Also an effort has been made to clarify the difference between rpm
and deb installations of Apache.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I11f92d91f4bdea884c266b91b52f9d012abd33b9
Partially-Implements: blueprint remove-web-eventlet

So it depends on cinder config already."}, {'account_id': 7505, 'date': '2015-05-11 13:42:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Matthew and Ken'ichi. Test is not skipped. I can guarantee. For our devstack-gate job, we define a very small services enabled, so we are a Networking plugin and we don't want to overload the OpenStack infrastructure as well as be save on our patches. Check out the services enabled here:

   https://github.com/openstack-infra/project-config/blob/master/jenkins/jobs/networking-midonet.yaml#L45

And, if you look at one of our patches, you can see the test is not skipped:

http://logs.openstack.org/92/177692/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet/2ead752/logs/testr_results.html.gz

(testVolumeBoot)"}, {'account_id': 7505, 'date': '2015-05-11 13:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I wanted to say "as well as save time on our patches" in previous comment.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-05-11 14:33:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Oh, the test is skipped there, the skip just happens a little bit later because it's per method instead of a class level exception so there are basic setup bits executed to create a user, tenant, and network for the tests which are then cleaned up right after. The network setup with your network driver is what is failing there:

http://logs.openstack.org/92/177692/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-networking-midonet/2ead752/console.html.gz#_2015-04-27_10_53_15_871

The test is skipped but your neutron driver is causing a 500 response before the run can reach raising the skip exception which is why you're seeing the traceback in the logs. Adding a 2nd skip prior to the already existing one will just mask the bug you're hitting (and probably just move it to elsewhere in the run)"}, {'account_id': 7505, 'date': '2015-05-11 14:36:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Oh. I understand now! Thanks for the clarification, Matthew!
I'll abandon this patch, then."}, {'account_id': 7505, 'date': '2015-05-11 14:38:20.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

It seems like this skip is not needed. As Matthew Treinish has pointed a couple of comments above.'}]

commit_message:
Skip scenario test when cinder is not available

When in `tempest.conf` we have:

[service_available]
cinder = False

`scenario.test_volume_boot_pattern` test should not run. This patch
skips the test by looking at `CFG.service_available.cinder` attribute.

Change-Id: Icd5d58ca0b6102d09b05c9e9fe4768f57d6bb69f

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-04 08:08:39.000000000', 'message': "Implement LBaaS MidoNet driver

Shift the implementation of LBaaS v1 from implementing inside
the monolithic plugin to the advanced service's driver model
so that it utilizes more upstream code.  As a consequence, the
following changes are included in this patch:

 * Since DB updates occur before the driver code is reached,
   change the validation logic of the pool-hm association
 * Similarly, update the LBaaS DB tables appropriately from
   the driver when validation errors occur
 * Split the driver into the API-based and the cluster-based
 * Organize the LBaaS unit tests so that both the cluster and
   API based driver tests run.
 * Set up devstack so that lbaas service is always enabled and
   sets the driver to the new MidoNet LBaaS driver.

Change-Id: Ifa82a02eb3458e1a145a028facb05526e65a83f6
Implements: MNP-115

commit_message:
Implement LBaaS MidoNet driver

Shift the implementation of LBaaS v1 from implementing inside
the monolithic plugin to the advanced service's driver model
so that it utilizes more upstream code.  As a consequence, the
following changes are included in this patch:

 * Since DB updates occur before the driver code is reached,
   change the validation logic of the pool-hm association
 * Similarly, update the LBaaS DB tables appropriately from
   the driver when validation errors occur
 * Split the driver into the API-based and the cluster-based
 * Organize the LBaaS unit tests so that both the cluster and
   API based driver tests run.
 * Set up devstack so that lbaas service is always enabled and
   sets the driver to the new MidoNet LBaaS driver.

Change-Id: Ifa82a02eb3458e1a145a028facb05526e65a83f6
Implements: MNP-115

Update name to [Beta] Community Application Catalog

The full name is "Community Application Catalog", and
the OpenStack Foundation has requested we add "beta"
before that full name. Also replaced tabs with spaces.

commit_message:
Add ironic-discoverd

We need to talk with ironic-discoverd in Tuskar UI in order to do
hardware discovery in TripleO. So far we did that manually, by calling
requests, but now, that it has a proper Python client library, we would
like to switch to using that.

Link to the package on PyPi:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/ironic-discoverd/1.0.0

Change-Id: I5ab19b08eef662b1babd20292cc28f5cf24d6fd8

For new Requirements
--------------------

- Is the library actively maintained?

  We *really* want some indication that the library is something we
  can get support on if we or our users find a bug, and that we
  don't have to take over and fork the library.

  Pointers to recent activity upstream and a consistent release model
  are appreciated.

- Is the library good code?

  It's expected, before just telling everyone to download arbitrary 3rd
  party code from the internet, that the submitter has taken a deep dive
  into the code to get a feel on whether this code seems solid enough
  to depend on. That includes ensuring the upstream code has some
  reasonable testing baked in.

- Is the library python 3 compatible?

  OpenStack will eventually need to support python 3. At this point
  adding non python 3 compatible libraries should only be done under
  *extreme* need. It should be considered a very big exception.

- Is the library license compatible?

  Preferably Apache2, BSD, MIT licensed. LGPL is ok. GPL or AGPL is
  verboten. Any other oddball license should be rejected.

- Is the library already packaged in the distros we target (Ubuntu
  latest / Fedora latest)?

  By adding something to OpenStack ``global-requirements.txt`` we are
  basically demanding that Linux Distros package this for the next
  release of OpenStack. If they already have, great. If not, we should
  be cautious of adding it. :ref:`finding-distro-status`

- Is the function of this library already covered by other libraries
  in ``global-requirements.txt``?

  Everyone has their own pet libraries that they like to use, but we
  do not need three different request mocking libraries in OpenStack.

  If this new requirement is about replacing an existing library with
  one that's better suited for our needs, then we also need the
  transition plan to drop the old library in a reasonable amount of
  time."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-04-24 18:05:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add cachetools requirement

What?
- cachetools provides python3 lru_cache decorator and
  some variants for all python versions.

Usage?
- taskflow (to expire a file cache)

Is the library actively maintained?
- Last modified dec 2014, so somewhat active

Is the library good code?
- Needs more docstrings, but structured well and has decent
  docs @ http://pythonhosted.org/cachetools/

Is the library python 3 compatible?
- Yes

Is the library license compatible?
- Yes, MIT licensed

Is the library already packaged in the distros we target?
- https://packages.debian.org/sid/python-cachetools
- https://launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/python-cachetools
- Does *not* currently seem to exist in fedora

Is the function of this library already covered by other
libraries in ``global-requirements.txt``?
- No

Change-Id: I31f5838ede9628ce25676381a35e974406a43a69

commit_message:
Update the minimum glanceclient version

A bug is present in glanceclient versions 0.16.1 and 0.17.0 which means
that https connections can not be established between nova and glance,
causing API requests to fail.

Bump the minimum supported version to prevent users hitting this issue.

Change-Id: Id10e46166b90e67b013512476fb546f463316a1e
Related-bug: 1442664

Most of Glance's current checks are implemented in the API controllers
but in Kilo, Glance added the ability to actually define meaningful
policy rules around images and image members. In an effort to harden
our default config as best as we can, we should check to see if the
user trying to perform some of these actions are either an admin or the
owner of the image.

Change-Id: I2dcf4d828c9be88143174de30a6b59d655ab0539
Closes-bug: 1408363
(cherry picked from commit 8bebbc6e530efe26c98f396b24c0ea00971093d3)
"}]
commit_message:
Harden our copy of Glance's policy

Most of Glance's current checks are implemented in the API controllers
but in Kilo, Glance added the ability to actually define meaningful
policy rules around images and image members. In an effort to harden
our default config as best as we can, we should check to see if the
user trying to perform some of these actions are either an admin or the
owner of the image.

Change-Id: I2dcf4d828c9be88143174de30a6b59d655ab0539
Closes-bug: 1408363
(cherry picked from commit 8bebbc6e530efe26c98f396b24c0ea00971093d3)

commit_message:
Require flake8 2.4.0

flake8 2.4.0 has support for marking hacking extensions as
off_by_default and then turning them on in tox.ini using the
select option in the flake8 stanza.

Patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/134052 will add using this
support to hacking.

Change-Id: I7f8ef22254703a53b73ccd048322191cfc677958

commit_message:
Introduce dependencies for Murano apps

This change-request introduce Depends On section for
Murano applications. If your application depends on some particular
base image or on other packages, you can state these dependencies
adding dependsOn section to application definition.

Example

     dependsOn:
        apps:
          - io.murano.databases.MySql
          - io.murano.apps.apache.ApacheHttpServer
          - io.murano.apps.ZabbixAgent
        image:
          name: Debian 8 x64 (pre-installed murano-agent)
          uri: http://storage.catalog.mirantis.com/images/debian-8-m-agent.qcow2

Change-Id: Id3535ceba39fe62682af80a391bb8bd3ab2254a0
Implements: blueprint murano-apps-dependencies

commit_message:
Document requirement to use separate RabbitMQ

For production environments, the RabbitMQ server used by Trove
should be different from the one used by the rest of the
OpenStack infrastructure, due to security concerns.

Change-Id: Ibbe4ae1185c8c0e18e14687d6fb558ceabd15ec1
Closes-bug: #1453194

commit_message:
Add apps from openstack/murano-apps

Following Murano applications from official murano-apps
repository were added to the catalog:
  * Apache HTTP Server
  * MySQL
  * PostgreSQL
  * SQLDatabase Library
  * Apache Tomcat
  * Wordpress
  * Zabbix Agent
  * Zabbix

Debian 8 x64 image with pre-installed with murano-agent used by this
applications is also added.

Change-Id: Id21e838a7bf793bf7b06f4177376991da770fbe9

commit_message:
Add Bandit as a global test requirement

Bandit is a new tool to do static analysis of openstack projects
for security issues.  Adding to global requirements so that other
projects make use it to find and fix potential security related
bugs.

Change-Id: I7273fbe42b52753cc297c683798252be5f3fd19b

commit_message:
Bump futures up to 3.0 or greater

The 3.0 release of futures removed support
for py2.5 and py3.1 and also enables the ability
to correctly retain the traceback of exceptions
on 2.x versions of python. This functionality
will enable much better exception tracking when
the futures/executor interface is used and would be
a welcome addition in futures using projects (and
helps aid the migration to 3.x which includes
tracebacks by default).

This release also fixes memory leaks, as_completed
and other various bugs that were previously occurring
with the 2.x branch.

The new home of this code also moved from google
code to https://github.com/agronholm/pythonfutures

Change-Id: I36f1241b983f6552d8bd0471e6a7485532a95a14

This runs through all of global-requirements.txt and looks at the
release history of all components over the last N days, returning the
released list. This is helpful in unexplained gate breaks to at least
look for candidate libraries.

Fleshed out some docs to explain intent for future consumers /
modifiers of this script.

Change-Id: I5880a1d7f0a6063a45f7533319fed1ff56057144
(cherry picked from commit 0c2eef0a4fbe35af084ec3af5d93685e60ba31ac)
'}]
commit_message:
add what-broke.py analayzer

This runs through all of global-requirements.txt and looks at the
release history of all components over the last N days, returning the
released list. This is helpful in unexplained gate breaks to at least
look for candidate libraries.

Fleshed out some docs to explain intent for future consumers /
modifiers of this script.

Change-Id: I5880a1d7f0a6063a45f7533319fed1ff56057144
(cherry picked from commit 0c2eef0a4fbe35af084ec3af5d93685e60ba31ac)

commit_message:
Make all pypy jobs non-voting

Per discussion on mailing list:
http://markmail.org/message/7xviqy3tvlefzrf7

We should just mark the jobs as non-voting for now
and remove them if the jobs are not fixed in a
reasonable time frame.

commit_message:
Configure minions properly

A previus commit introduced a regression which caused kubectl not
to configure properly.  This results in kube minions staying in the
NotReady state and this script not completing execution.

Change-Id: I336c21ac2660c4c19c401b8ecbd8015cc44dbfdd
Closes-Bug: #1453470
(cherry picked from commit 8d7e4a4ab4da3b54fb5ecc246d938d3c745bcbad)

commit_message:
Fix KeystoneV2Credentials import error

Original tempest.auth has been moved to tempest_lib.auth:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/166022/

We should correct KeystoneV2Credentials import module path to tempest_lib.auth

Change-Id: I0299d77d940133908555627bbaec23ac5d667f1e

commit_message:
Correct directories check for N327 hacking check

For some reason the N327 hacking heck was looking for
cinder.unit/tests and cinder.functional/tests in the filename
that is sent in for the hacking check.  This should be
cinder/tests/unit and cinder/tests/functional.

This concern was originally raised in this review:
https://review.openstack.org/175604

Change-Id: Ic3041d9e16b3707aaf42ff941206d24ec66ead2b

commit_message:
make pypy non-voting across the board

This is breaking at a fundamental level on all jobs. We should disable
voting for pypy across the board to get things moving again, and
consider removing this in the future.

Consolidate the multiple definitions for pypy that would be created
with this, and place the comments next to the correct logical blocks
to make them less confusing.

Related-Bug: #1290562

Change-Id: If1cf7af0e950f9b7725e84127ee936bffd63ea6d

commit_message:
Update rc manifest parsing according to v1beta3

Now that Kubernetes 0.15.0 release is supported and it has
v1beta3, the manifest structure has changed from v1beta1 to
v1beta3. This change implements the v1beta3 manifest parsing
logic for rc resource of Kubernetes.

Change-Id: I54aa0502c6d9a58652623800e02766ad5b09b159
Partially-Implements: blueprint python-k8sclient
(cherry picked from commit 4d7a38d3af9ba350b81bc834b94222b625d222c4)

(1 comment)

I believe I see the problem now. Using the `build-all-docker-images` script without specifying the "latest" tag leads to confusion. In this case, the base image is built and tagged with the reference to git HEAD, but then when another build process is trying to pull the base image it used the "latest" tag for it, which is non-existent. 

I see two ways to improve the situation:
- stop defaulting to a reference to git HEAD and default to "latest" instead in build-docker-image. `build-all-docker-images` with no args will work out of the box, but the problem remains when building with a different tag.
- allow specifying the tag that is picked up for the parent image, and defaulting that to the current build tag (the one specified, or current git HEAD otherwise). Problem: how to build "my_image:my_tag" based on "base_image:latest"?

An hybrid solution would be to make the tag propagation to parent image optional and use it by default in `build-all-docker-images` script. Opinions?

As a workaround, I suggest you always call `build-all-docker-images` using the "-t latest" switch.'}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2015-05-04 16:04:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-04 16:19:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Update error message for build-docker-images

When using the build-all-docker-images script the script will
build images that pull from a base image.  By default, Docker
is looking for that base image with the tag 'latest'.  If you
are building into you own namespace for the first time you will
likely not have all of the base images built with the tag 'latest'.

For example, if I build to my namespace for the first time.
The image rthallisey/centos-rdo-glance-base will be build and pushed.
Then, the image rthallisey/centos-rdo-glance-base:latest will be
pulled in order to build rthallisey/centos-rdo-glance-api and Docker
will fail to find that image.

The solution is to alert the user to tell Docker to look for a
specific tag or when building, add the argument '-t latest'.

Change-Id: I29d41db0a413fc57e3b919e4f974e4ef2b8b99c2

commit_message:
Pin version to 2015.1.0

Neutron has already been released, but our plugin not yet. We need to
pin the version to don't have to handle incompatibilities on our current
development.

Change-Id: Ie928a7a49a3924f4e53d91138e60af712b853ca2

[{'created': '2015-04-03 14:05:12.000000000', 'message': 'Windows iSCSI: fix volume clone

In some environments, volume cloning fails when using the Windows
iSCSI volume driver. This involves creating a new VHD image and
copying the data from the source volume on top.

This can raise an error, caused by the fact that the destination
path exists.

This patch slightly changes the workflow used when cloning an image.
Instead of first creating a new WT disk and then copying the cloned
image data on top, the source image is copied, resized if needed
and then imported as a WT disk.

(cherry picked from commit fed458ef1ad367ef38196b92b9e87562bcc7bda6)

Change-Id: I07d45fa9324a34ef45ed2aa8051338ee6a0f8a5b
Closes-Bug: #1435865
'}]
commit_message:
Windows iSCSI: fix volume clone

In some environments, volume cloning fails when using the Windows
iSCSI volume driver. This involves creating a new VHD image and
copying the data from the source volume on top.

This can raise an error, caused by the fact that the destination
path exists.

This patch slightly changes the workflow used when cloning an image.
Instead of first creating a new WT disk and then copying the cloned
image data on top, the source image is copied, resized if needed
and then imported as a WT disk.

(cherry picked from commit fed458ef1ad367ef38196b92b9e87562bcc7bda6)

Change-Id: I07d45fa9324a34ef45ed2aa8051338ee6a0f8a5b
Closes-Bug: #1435865

subject: Windows iSCSI driver: Fixes copy disk method exception handling

commit_message:
Windows iSCSI driver: Fixes copy disk method exception handling

In the copy_vhd_disk method, it is assumed that if the copy operation
fails, a wmi.x_wmi exception will be raised. This is wrong. In fact,
none of the methods called there can raise such an exception in those
circumstances.

At the moment, this method will not raise an exception even if the
copy operation fails.

This patch adds a check to see if the source image actually exists.
The according CIM_DataFile Copy method's return value is checked as
well in order to see if the operation failed or not.

(cherry picked from commit b5567ed10a2e49adca849456049393120e375965)

Change-Id: I778ecd61adb007995b629b36044caac78cd16889
Closes-Bug: #1356398

commit_message:
Propose translations: Fix handling of deleted files

Today's propose_translation_update.sh run failed for ceilometer since
files were deleted but the loop in filter_commit considered these
as zero changing lines. Change the loop to check only new and modified
files.

Change-Id: I94f5389b9fe0c16d529860f57bb63ef8a3c5c64a

commit_message:
change default value for glance/vmware_api_retry_count

There is the bug with ostf tests for glance. Test fails if it tries to
do something when auth session restarts. A part of solution is to
increase timeouts for steps of ostf tests. Second one is change
defaults for vmware_api_retry_count to increase of times glance retry
on failures.

Change-Id: Ia2d2c320fbb52ed7cc77a2396c57d42e78cd1173
Partial-Bug: #1437228

commit_message:
Added dangling mock detection to 'network' module

Ensured that no dangling mocks exist in the module by having each test
class extend trove_testtools.TestCase

Ran 'tox -epy27' and fixed any detected problems.

Change-Id: I065df61c09d7c579a5e1386fc96a546949f54d77
Partial-Bug: 1448273

[{'created': '2015-02-25 17:25:01.000000000', 'message': 'Fix possibility of data leakage for commom X-Versions-Location

When two or mre containers send their versioned files to the same
location it is possible for objects with the same name, from
different containers to get repleced in the wrong container. The
name of the source container was prepended to the old versions
to avoid this confusion. Backwards compatibility was taken into
account as the new routine checks for old versions with the old-
fashioned naming.

Change-Id: I7e8f8f8a16a89979ac361ba4712babe344f5cf0b
Closes-Bug: #1138531
'}]
commit_message:
Fix possibility of data leakage for commom X-Versions-Location

When two or mre containers send their versioned files to the same
location it is possible for objects with the same name, from
different containers to get repleced in the wrong container. The
name of the source container was prepended to the old versions
to avoid this confusion. Backwards compatibility was taken into
account as the new routine checks for old versions with the old-
fashioned naming.

Change-Id: I7e8f8f8a16a89979ac361ba4712babe344f5cf0b
Closes-Bug: #1138531

'}, {'created': '2015-04-29 05:30:33.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] Add errexit to setup & cleanup functions

It is too easy to introduce errors into the gate scripts and not
notice; for example see Icd853c670dfd9bd067f472203b38dd258d90e8ba.  To
find problems like this, set errexit for the setup & cleanup helper
functions.

To facilitate this more cleanly we add a little helper function that
creates the commands.

tsfilter is modified to return the status of the first command, not
the awk filter.  This is important to actually catch any errors from
what it is running.

Some minor tweaks to the setup scripts to make them safe are added.
cleanup_host is left for another change to avoid too much churn.

Note setting errexit globally in the devstck-vm-gate-wrap.sh script is
a little more trouble than it is worth; since the testing commands are
expected to fail if there is a problem, we need to continue with the
script to clean-up and copy the logs out.

You might think, hey, we could get around that by doing some variation
of

  a_function && rc=$? || rc=$?
  cleanup_fn
  return $rc

but there is a small trap with that -- running as part of a "&&" or
"||" pipeline disables errexit for "a_function" -- thus by setting
errexit in the calling script, we effectively disable ourselves from
using it in functions we call that might fail!  This is a problem as
we're using bash functions as hooks all over the place.

Change-Id: Ia791b8bdb9fef5d5c41702eaa8b43c2e94b8499b

commit_message:
Add errexit to setup & cleanup functions

It is too easy to introduce errors into the gate scripts and not
notice; for example see Icd853c670dfd9bd067f472203b38dd258d90e8ba.  To
find problems like this, set errexit for the setup & cleanup helper
functions.

To facilitate this more cleanly we add a little helper function that
creates the commands.

Dependent changes should have made the scripts errexit clean.
cleanup_host is left for another change to avoid too much churn.

Note setting errexit globally in the devstck-vm-gate-wrap.sh script is
a little more trouble than it is worth; since the testing commands are
expected to fail if there is a problem, we need to continue with the
script to clean-up and copy the logs out.

You might think, hey, we could get around that by doing some variation
of

  a_function && rc=$? || rc=$?
  cleanup_fn
  return $rc

but there is a small trap with that -- running as part of a "&&" or
"||" pipeline disables errexit for "a_function" -- thus by setting
errexit in the calling script, we effectively disable ourselves from
using it in functions we call that might fail!  This is a problem as
we're using bash functions as hooks all over the place.

Change-Id: Ia791b8bdb9fef5d5c41702eaa8b43c2e94b8499b

commit_message:
Return command status in tsfilter

Make sure to return the command status, not the status of the awk.
This is important for picking up errors with errexit.

Change-Id: Id5bd81f22678d23f72d5188267ff171d59e1a9ae

We already have a local copy of the git repos in /opt/git and the
hacking integration test can use an arbitrary repo path by setting
REPO_ROOT. Since we don't need the target-project repo to super up to
date just use the local copy to stop cloning across the network.

Change-Id: I3c751934f082007e1bc86dc9ed4cc22afd79f369
"}]
commit_message:
Stop hacking integration test from cloning across the network

We already have a local copy of the git repos in /opt/git and the
hacking integration test can use an arbitrary repo path by setting
REPO_ROOT. Since we don't need the target-project repo to super up to
date just use the local copy to stop cloning across the network.

Change-Id: I3c751934f082007e1bc86dc9ed4cc22afd79f369

commit_message:
Remove integrated-gate template from sahara

Now that sahara has its own job that runs just the sahara tests in
tempest, stop running tempest-full jobs from the integrated-gate on
sahara.

This will remove:
* tempest-dsvm-full
* tempest-dsvm-postgres-full
* tempest-dsvm-neutron-full

Change-Id: I1f89a4e6aa40250f5d036dcc98b59c0526e80995

I dont think wrapping should be necessary - if we end up wanting to in the future we can subclass Bunch like you say and it shouldnt break backwards compat.'}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2015-05-09 05:22:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'm not sure why we want to do this. The methods are meant to return a dict so it can be used as one. Can you give some more rationale please?"}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-05-09 12:15:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

The intent here is that we let a bunch of the underlying python-*client objects slip through the API for a while, which means there's a non-zero amount of code that depends on attribute access. The effective API actually winds up being identical if we use Bunch - so that consuming code that uses server.name can still use server.name, and new code that uses server['name'] can also work.

The reason for converting to dicts originally was for easy serialization to yaml. commit_message:
Return Bunch objects instead of plain dicts

Bunch objects are dot-accessible dictionaries, so we can say
server.name or server['name'] equally.

commit_message:
Adding create permissions to networking-vsphere

This modification is needed so that networking-vsphere-release team
can create branches. Config file described in [1] lacks this rule,
so this was omitted during the creation of the project.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/creators.html#add-gerrit-permissions

Change-Id: I36aafb6d5e8d7446649179ace5a21441a296b8a6

commit_message:
Update jenkins jobs for networking-ovn

networking-ovn has been running a simple devstack job for a while that
installs OVN and brings up Neutron using OVN as a backend.  It at
least ensures things don't blow up on startup or when the default
networks are created by devstack.  Rename this job
(s/tempest/install/) and make it voting.

Create a new non-voting job that actually runs tempest so we can start
working through whatever blows up there.

Change-Id: I6481e47a88311c9124e3286a848b9bcaddf1371b

test_setup_events_default_config unnecessarily mocks os.path.exists.
this seems to be causing failures when running tox -edebug --
test_setup_events_default_config (and occasionally in gate). it's
dangerous to mock os.path because other libs might depend on it so
let's stop mocking it.

Closes-Bug: #1449604
"}]
commit_message:
stop mocking os.path in test_setup_events_default_config

test_setup_events_default_config unnecessarily mocks os.path.exists.
this seems to be causing failures when running tox -edebug --
test_setup_events_default_config (and occasionally in gate). it's
dangerous to mock os.path because other libs might depend on it so
let's stop mocking it.

Change-Id: Ibe9027874f597348c5da6c92899cf8740eb678c2
Closes-Bug: #1449604

commit_message:
Cleanup openstack documentation Gerrit ACLs

api-site and openstack-manuals share the same permissions, use only one
config file.

Remove not needed "refs/heads/stable/" sections, these are not needed
with current gerrit project setup, we inherit from "refs/heads/" and the
permissions are the same.

This is a cleanup, there should not be any functional change for any of
these repositories.

Change-Id: Iba09f6ea8618740790ae51ecbf08010adb4f432e

commit_message:
Fix delete_server when wait=True

Functional tests were running with wait=False, which hid that we
are not handling the expected NotFound error after delete. So we
refactor delete_server to use get_server and be much simpler. Note that
we call the ServerGet task directly since we already have the ID that we
want to make sure we deleted, no need for listing at that point.

Adding unit test coverage to help avoid these problems in the future as
well.

Change-Id: Ib78aef75a5ad3f75bc8ee2b81078d30cc2fc76db

commit_message:
VMware: Allow other nested hypervisors (HyperV)

The vmware driver already detects when the os type of an instance
is ESX and sets the nested hypervisor virtualization flag.  The
same should be done for when HyperV is the os type of the instance.

Change-Id: I05da223036998c7705e7cdcceab221de490a4d05

commit_message:
Ironic hypervisor should not be counted when in maintenance status

Currently ironic hypervisor is still available when the node is in
maintenance status, so add a filter to correct this.

Change-Id: I3141c5c652c0f77e7134fa21639eaf6cde7b1fde
Closes-bug: #1435153

commit_message:
Check resolver pip on global-requirements changes

This nonvoting job should flag failures or regressions in
co-installability using the resolver branch of pip. We'll need this
until that is in a release.

Change-Id: I7600fa20391bb83491d630b277bf01cc3a20727c

commit_message:
tests: replace mox by mox3, clean out mox usage

This patch replaces mox3 by mox, so we can drop mox from requirements
and bring Python 3 compatibility. It also clear some mox usage and
use the fixture brought by oslotest.

Change-Id: Ia242425815b09e1e67d33702f1e5dbe6bcd599fd

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary oauth_api check

Since the class uses dependency.requires, the oauth_api field will
always be set, so there's no need to check it.

Change-Id: If39b84c7d41be77a8248263d51d2e249bddce802

commit_message:
Use short names for drivers

With stevedore support, we can use shorter names for the drivers
rather than the full class path.

Using the full class path is supported, but deprecated (the code
falls back to importing by importutils which is already reported
as deprecated).

bp stevedore

Co-Authored-By: Boris Bobrov <bbobrov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I11cf1bca474f59419185e2a1970c1dae31017329

subject: Use stevedore for backend drivers

commit_message:
Use stevedore for backend drivers

The Stevedore library is used for loading backend drivers rather
than using importutils. This provides a level of indirection for
deployers/packagers.

The importutils method of loading drivers is still supported, but
it's deprecated.

bp stevedore

Change-Id: Id77ebf7056987ff1d3b9f62fab411845e63c86c3

commit_message:
Use instance.save to update instance

when instance is updating, we can use instance.save
directly in compute layer, also when set to scheduling
state, we don't need to call RT update.

Change-Id: Idd3a322a7fe1b3e67af9ffe29372faece80c562e

Still need to verify that the centralizer IPV6 actually works

Close-Bug: #1450320
Change-Id: Iac7a62a5e6074d2b55820056224d8290b4b62f38

commit_message:
Support for working with IPV6
1) Offload the Ipv6 tarffic into the NORMAL path
2) Make sure we do not get exception and we know to handle IPV6 subnets

Add entry in the classifier table to offload the IPV6 traffic into the NORMAL
path until we add ipv6 support

Still need to verify that the centralizer IPV6 actually works

Close-Bug: #1450320
Change-Id: Iac7a62a5e6074d2b55820056224d8290b4b62f38

[{'created': '2015-05-07 16:29:05.000000000', 'message': "Ensure the indexer is disconnected in gabbi fixtures

An index.connect() was added in commit 0620d841 but no corresponding
disconnect(). There's evidence that not properly disposing of the
associated engine facade may be causing test failures when
sufficient gabbi fixtures end up in the same process (this requires
a relatively low number of available cores).

Even if the lack of disconnect is not the cause of that, it is still
a correct thing to have.

Change-Id: I53d6ffbdead5ee959521131aecb2d7b58b6f8dd6
"}]
commit_message:
Ensure the indexer is disconnected in gabbi fixtures

An index.connect() was added in commit 0620d841 but no corresponding
disconnect(). There's evidence that not properly disposing of the
associated engine facade may be causing test failures when
sufficient gabbi fixtures end up in the same process (this requires
a relatively low number of available cores).

Even if the lack of disconnect is not the cause of that, it is still
a correct thing to have.

Change-Id: I53d6ffbdead5ee959521131aecb2d7b58b6f8dd6

        return port_id_specified, subnet_id_specified

'port_id_specified' can be True only if 'port_id' not in 'interface_info'. If only 'subnet_id' is provided in the request, add_by_subnet will be used instead of add_by_port. commit_message:
Comments about _validate_interface_info is out of date

'add_by_port' will be False if no 'port_id' in the request, so
the comment is out of date.

Change-Id: I4082ee36732f72e97e721d81b2a7df275c4d7971

commit_message:
Adopt the John Papa Style Guide for AngularJS

This patch adds documentation recomending the John Papa Style guide.
Other patches may add automated style checks to JSCS.

Change-Id: Iae2cec88d8ea3c4ad570e1a1a42c5046bfef0dec
Implements: blueprint john-papa-style-guide

(1 comment)

I don't like the idea of adding a new API and support for a new console that only one hypervisor supports. At the very least I would like to see another hypervisor have adding WebMKS support on there tentative roadmap."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2014-10-16 08:40:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Joe, I agree purely from the perspective of the API. However, there is a precedent already: get_rdp_console is supported only by the hyperv driver.

I believe the real issue here is that the original api, get_vnc_console, had the console type in the name. It should have been called get_console. It already takes a type argument so that it can return different console types. There is no reason that rdp and webmks could not be additional types.

From a purely pragmatic point of view, supporting webmks is absolutely the right thing to do. VMware's support for VNC is shockingly bad, to the point that deploying it requires taking ESX hosts out of official support by the strictest definition. Enabling it in the driver requires working around a lack of extremely basic functionality, and has already resulted in several race conditions. Each of these allowed a user of one instance to view the console of another.

Before Radoslav pointed out to me that there's also a get_rdp_console, my original proposal was to add this as an additional type to get_vnc_console. That option is still available, however given that get_rdp_console exists it would not be consistent. If we want to tidy this up, we could consolidate the 2 existing get_<type>_console apis and add webmks as a new type.

However, whatever solution we choose, it shouldn't prevent us from supporting the hypervisor's native console protocol."}, {'account_id': 9172, 'date': '2014-10-16 08:43:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

@Joe Regarding your comment about adding a new API -- we have a dedicated API for getting an RDP console which is supported only by HyperV, so why not having an API for VMware consoles?

I am also fine to implement WebMKS as another type of VNC console (as Matt Booth suggested) in which case we won't need a new API. However, seeing the API for RDP, I thought this is the consistent way to implement this."}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2014-10-17 15:36:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think I like jo's point.

Ideally we would have a single API where you can get novnc, rdp, webkms, or whatever, ideally the server lists which are possible, and if you don't specify any, you get the default for that specific server, and it tells you the type in the response.

But maybe thats too much to force on this blueprint, but it feels like the right way forward. I need to think about that for a bit. This could be a good thing to bring up during an unconference slot at the summit."}, {'account_id': 9172, 'date': '2014-10-20 08:43:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 08:48:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

I like John's idea.


"Ideally we would have a single API where you can get novnc, rdp, webkms, or whatever, ideally the server lists which are possible, and if you don't specify any, you get the default for that specific server, and it tells you the type in the response.

But maybe thats too much to force on this blueprint, but it feels like the right way forward. I need to think about that for a bit. This could be a good thing to bring up during an unconference slot at the summit."

Agreed, this would make a good thing to talk about in one of the unconference slots. I am leaning towards:

* Require a blueprint to consolidate the get_console commands first (as John described).
* Formulate some policy about required console types etc. Having every backend support a different console type is really bad IMHO, and we should stop doing that.'}, {'account_id': 9172, 'date': '2014-12-11 15:05:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 9172, 'date': '2014-12-11 15:07:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
VMware: Native HTML5 consoles for VMware

This is a proposal to add support for the native HTML5 console available in
vSphere 5.5 and later (referred as WebMKS console). This will solve some of the
current problems that we have with VNC consoles with respect to deployment,
scalability and security. The existing support for VNC consoles will remain but
users will be encouraged to use WebMKS when possible.

blueprint vmware-webmks-console

Change-Id: Ie8e4d6f1091e2e48848952d6e0018e20990188aa

commit_message:
Windows iSCSI: remove ensure_export

The ensure_export method is called by the manager when the service
is initialized, ensuring that in-use volumes are properly exported.

iSCSI targets exported by WinTarget persist after host reboot.
For this reason, the ensure_export method can simply pass, thus
simplifying the iSCSI target creation logic.

The patch set depending on this introduces CHAP credentials support.
If the iSCSI target is accidentaly deleted, the CHAP credentials
will change, so the volume won't be accessible anyway if the target
is recreated using ensure_export.

Change-Id: I29367fc0ef0e38bb06c4a0ff5a485274cc29660e

commit_message:
Add dragonflow repository to Neutron

According to procedure defined in [1], this patch proposes Neutron
to embrace dragonflow within its fold.
Same as patches [2], [3] and [4].

Dragonflow is a L3 DVR implementation using SDN framework (Ryu)
which eliminate the need for using namespaces or local agents in the compute
node.
It uses Openflow to build packet pipeline and in the future can be used
to distribute north-south traffic and also eliminate L2 agent in compute node.
Currently Dragonflow is build on top of Neutron reference "legacy" L3 implementation
and can "fallback" to it in case of controller downtime.
(leverage current HA implementation)

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/doc/source/devref/sub_projects.rst
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179454/1
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179457/
[4] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/175954/

Change-Id: I079033207fc89b6ba3af547adda26ecaa917641c

commit_message:
Define validation_resources function for ssh validation

This patch implements changes needed to setup validation resources
for verifying ssh access to VM.

Partially implements: blueprint ssh-auth-strategy

Change-Id: I61d7e12ee842165006a2e0c5f74b8c513c3e57b2

commit_message:
Add networking-odl repo to Neutron

Similar to Russell's OVN patch, the networking-odl repository
is the backend code which handles communication with OpenDaylight.

For more information on networking-odl:
  https://github.com/stackforge/networking-odl/blob/master/README.rst

Related docs about adding repositories like this to Neutron can
be found here:
  https://review.openstack.org/175952

Change-Id: I81408301c78474f9da0bad23bf83bf6178160a9a

commit_message:
Instance ID was corrected

Regarding with RFC3986 percent character '%' must be followed by the two
hexadecimal digits. In other cases WSGI server can reject such  request.

Change-Id: I284091afd4e1e28c9c66972d15eeb105b9ba9217

commit_message:
Add networking-vsphere repo to Neutron

According to procedure defined in [1], this patch proposes Neutron
to embrace networking-vsphere within its fold. This project is about
adding Neutron support to the vsphere hypervisor technology using
opensource management/control/data plane elements like OVS.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/doc/source/devref/sub_projects.rst

Change-Id: Ia66799cda81f952c8fa244fdc23e17b9593e08ad

commit_message:
Add networking-l2gw repo to Neutron

According to procedure defined in [1], this patch proposes Neutron
to embrace networking-l2gw within its fold. This project is about
bridging virtual deployments with physical ones, and it is implemented
leveraging OVS and OVSDB.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/doc/source/devref/sub_projects.rst

Change-Id: I50051be2bba2460e7163903c165a158f11917729

[{'created': '2015-05-05 23:47:21.000000000', 'message': "Ensure that wheels are built with cffi 0.9.2

DevStack creates a virtual environment to build wheel packages. These packages
have external dependencies, but they don't respect OpenStack requirements: a
more recent version may be used.

xattr requires cffi. cffi 1.0beta1 was just released. xattr wheel package is
built with cffi 1.0beta1 whereas the wheel package will be used with cffi 0.9.2
installed on the system. As a consequence, importing xattr fails because cffi
cannot find the internal xattr library built by cffi. The internal library
filename is computed using the cffi version, and the cffi version mismatch:
0.9.2 vs 1.0beta1.

Workaround the issue by enforcing cffi 0.9.2 in the virtual environment used to
build wheel packages.

This issue is a quickfix to unblock gates. A better fix will be to enhance
tools/build_wheels.sh to respect OpenStack requirements (ex: cffi 0.9.2).

Change-Id: Iccb1416042cdf922ce8633d01b1904d9c067ad70
Closes-Bug: #1451992
"}]
commit_message:
Ensure that wheels are built with cffi 0.9.2

DevStack creates a virtual environment to build wheel packages. These packages
have external dependencies, but they don't respect OpenStack requirements: a
more recent version may be used.

xattr requires cffi. cffi 1.0beta1 was just released. xattr wheel package is
built with cffi 1.0beta1 whereas the wheel package will be used with cffi 0.9.2
installed on the system. As a consequence, importing xattr fails because cffi
cannot find the internal xattr library built by cffi. The internal library
filename is computed using the cffi version, and the cffi version mismatch:
0.9.2 vs 1.0beta1.

Workaround the issue by enforcing cffi 0.9.2 in the virtual environment used to
build wheel packages.

This issue is a quickfix to unblock gates. A better fix will be to enhance
tools/build_wheels.sh to respect OpenStack requirements (ex: cffi 0.9.2).

Change-Id: Iccb1416042cdf922ce8633d01b1904d9c067ad70
Closes-Bug: #1451992

commit_message:
Add Octavia repo to Neutron

Similar to Russell's OVN patch, the Octavia repository is a backend for
neutron's lbaas, targeted to be the new reference implementation in
Liberty.

For more information on Octavia:
  https://github.com/stackforge/octavia/tree/master/doc/source

And related docs about adding repositories like this to Neutron can
be found here:
  https://review.openstack.org/175952

Change-Id: If705f04986de92d386bc7f10a94a5c14eeed7697

commit_message:
Fix verify_tempest_config to not leak a tenant

When admin was available with tenant isolation, this script was
creating an isolated tenant but not clearing it.

Change-Id: Ie87cd3902ee645de173f50838e6df9a1ff4eb534

[{'created': '2015-04-16 17:16:27.000000000', 'message': "Cleanup exception usage and logging calls in fixed_networks

This commit cleans up some uses of the NotFound exception from
tempest-lib. This exception is RestClientException and is only expected
to be used with a 404 response. It was previously just used as a local
exception to trigger the same failure path as if a 404 was received.
For clarity this changes that exception to raise an InvalidConfiguration
instead, because the raises are caused by an invalid network name being
provided in configuration (either through the fixed_network_name option
or the accounts.yaml file) At the same time as this logging calls are
made more consistent. There isn't a functional change, the usage pattern
is just made consistent in the module.

commit_message:
Rework get_network_from_name() function

This commit reworks the logic in the get_network_from_name() function
to make what it's doing a bit easier to follow. Instead of returning
either the expected response or an incomplete response given a failure
this instead will raise an InvalidException instead. The callers of the
function are then updated to handle that exception appropriately.

As part of this it cleans up some uses of the NotFound exception from
tempest-lib. This exception is RestClientException and is only expected
to be used with a 404 response. It was previously just used as a local
exception to trigger the same failure path as if a 404 was received.
For clarity this changes that exception to raise an InvalidConfiguration
instead, because the raises are caused by an invalid network name being
provided in configuration (either through the fixed_network_name option
or the accounts.yaml file) At the same time as this logging calls are
made more consistent.

Change-Id: I709dce36210efa9038ce2d98328fc1740d9bf493

commit_message:
Fix leaked mocks in the 'upgrade' module if any

Make all test suites in the module extend 'trove_testtools.TestCase' to
enable dangling mock detector.

I also rewrote tests for 'create()' method of 'UpgradeMessageSender'.
The original implementation tested the Mock library rather than the
Trove code.

Change-Id: I862b9b6c3dbca1958f314b169863cdbeeb7e3b53
Partial-Bug: 1448273

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-21 15:55:20.000000000', 'message': 'Add networking-ovn repo to Neutron.

The networking-ovn repository is a Neutron driver for connecting to
OVN.  OVN is virtual networking control plane being rapidly developed
as a part of the Open vSwitch project.  For more information about
OVN:

  http://networkheresy.com/2015/01/13/ovn-bringing-native-virtual-networking-to-ovs/
  http://blog.russellbryant.net/category/ovn/

During the Kilo development cycle, the Neutron team initiated an
effort referred to as "plugin decomposition".  The spec for that is
here:

  http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/neutron-specs/specs/kilo/core-vendor-decomposition.html

I would say that the primary issue being addressed by this effort is
development scalability.  It is one method that allows a separate
review team to manage the development of driver code.

This split created a number of new git repositories.  Most of these
new repositories are in Stackforge.  However, it is my opinion that
many (if not most, or even all) of these repositories make sense to be
considered under the Neutron team in terms of project governance.
They are development efforts that help fulfill the Neutron mission
statement.

This patch only proposes the move of one repo, as I think the team
managing each repo should take some action to confirm they would like
to be considered part of the Neutron project, and the Neutron PTL
should ACK each one.

It's understandable that the Neutron team doesn't want to reintroduce
development bottleneck issues that the split was intended to address.
A Neutron devref patch discussing this particular point is here:

  https://review.openstack.org/175952

The alternative to this would be to create new project teams with a
PTL for each Neutron driver, or to not consider Neutron driver code to
be an OpenStack project.

Change-Id: I153a5b4f89677b070aa8d038b04e9c35a1cc2fa9

commit_message:
Add networking-ovn repo to Neutron.

The networking-ovn repository is a Neutron driver for connecting to
OVN.  OVN is virtual networking control plane being rapidly developed
as a part of the Open vSwitch project.  For more information about
OVN:

  http://networkheresy.com/2015/01/13/ovn-bringing-native-virtual-networking-to-ovs/
  http://blog.russellbryant.net/category/ovn/

Some related docs about adding repositories like this to Neutron can
be found here:

  https://review.openstack.org/175952

Change-Id: I153a5b4f89677b070aa8d038b04e9c35a1cc2fa9

commit_message:
Fix retyping attached volumes requiring migration

Modifies retype method so that volume db entry only updated if the
volume isn't migrated.

The migrate_volume_completion method is made responsible for detaching
the old volume and attaching the new one. This takes the requirement
from nova because the calls need to be done in a certain order which
isn't guaranteed when performed by nova.

attach_volume now marks the migration_status as complete because it is
the final action by cinder.

(cherry picked from commit 31ad23c4820048ca13e0948e28d2a90ad228b09c)

Partial-Bug: 1316079
Change-Id: Ia15636893be4f0077a4f75e746a8ab1a8798c44b

commit_message:
Fixes migrate_volume_completion

The following issues are addressed:

The source volume is never deleted when a migration is done because
status_update was assumed to always be a dict.

Unattached volumes are set to in-use when retyped.

In-use migrated volumes are left in status attaching.

(cherry picked from commit 910575997ef9700ef2482705d79a1df013c7e554)

Conflicts:
	cinder/tests/test_volume.py
	cinder/volume/manager.py

Partial-Bug: 1316079
Change-Id: Ib5034679a5f469ba53e6280a47e8c94d633cf911

commit_message:
Allow the ldap scheme to be configurable

Some people may need to use secure ldap. In that case, they should be
able to provide their own ldap scheme for the URI, e.g., ldaps.

Change-Id: I5e168f3bd51e8325024570df440aa11c9a28d57d
Closes-bug: 1453342

commit_message:
remove router interface on Arista L3 plugin fails

The failure is because of mismatch of the
parameters to _validate_interface_info(). This patch removes
this code as it can be inherited from upstream

Change-Id: I5a92c6d05876e9ab5201e8fac018433eeb5c89e4
Closes-Bug: #1453323

commit_message:
Revert "Use iptables zone to separate different ip_conntrack"

This reverts commit bd5373b670cdd7f21f8a1ece98fde6be9fda71ab.

There has been a spike in gate failures related to VM connectivity
since this was merged. Until this is root-caused and solved in
Idb1577128be5d8812024467f599166bc131d57ea, I think we should
probably revert this to improve the stability of the gate.

Change-Id: I346dc0c3bfb02c34fc85f5f91c94d4fedbd32bbe

commit_message:
show error traceback only for debug mode

ironicclient shows traceback always for some commands fails, this bug add
the logic to control client show traceback only on debug mode

Change-Id: I527f30defbcf8616886a46251e2ff88e4715ca81
Closes-Bug: 1447856

- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/97/180397/2/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha/ed02d25/ : SUCCESS in 1h 18m 59s'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2015-05-06 06:24:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

It was intentional given the semantics of AWS snapshots. In AWS, snapshots are independent of volume lifecycle and remain there after volume deletion (IIRC). It's not the case in Cinder, so using backups for that purpose made more sense."}, {'account_id': 8289, 'date': '2015-05-06 07:13:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Thomas Herve:
Thanks, but what I fix is creation volume from snapshot, the status in cinder is:
1. create volume1
2. snapshot the volume1 -> snapshot1
3. the volume1 can't deleted because the snapshot1
4. create volume2 from snapshot1
5. the snapshot1 and volume2 are dependent, you can delete snapshot1 or delete the volume2

So, for volume resource, the 'snapshot' should be snapshot not backup. If for snapshot resource creation, when create snapshot from volume, I think we should create a backup."}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2015-05-06 07:26:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sorry, I don't understand how's that relevant.

Another argument to keep the behavior as-is is that if you set DELETION_POLICY to SNAPSHOT, you end up with a backup, which you can then feed to a future volume."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-10 23:57:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 8289, 'date': '2015-05-11 07:48:45.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Don't treated 'SnapshotId' as backup_id

Create volume from snapshot instead backup when
user specify 'SnapshotId' for EC2 volume.

Change-Id: Icc06a47fa705e6f473db6756c7bdd730f2c6af84
Closes-Bug: #1452094

Restore old ruby exclusion for 6.0 compatibility

In 6.0 we need to exclude ruby-2.1.1* packages while
installing Ruby during classic provisioning.

Closes-bug: #1453206

commit_message:

Related-bug: #1436414

Commit d6cff81273fe05e59ac0b0a4c7f94cb56d648f86 was merged without addressing my comments. I would like to understand whether resource cleanup will or will not really affect production deployments.

commit_message:
Ensure *-show input uuid is not empty

Ironic *-show does not ensure that uuid are not empty.

This patch adds checks to the client to ensure that command line
arguments are not empty strings or only whitespace. It will raise
a command exception if *-show command line argument is an empty
string or only whitespace.

Change-Id: Ia34957922006da5ecbbfc7483040d67ac51f0ada
Closes-Bug: 1442436
(cherry picked from commit cec37d5a67b2500263e033b7241606174513a38f)

Encode exception on cli for UnicodeDecodeError

cli did not handle output exception which is encoded,this patch
implements the shell encoding for exception output.

"}, {'created': '2015-05-06 02:34:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix false NotFound errors in Huawei driver

Fix huawei driver that 'AllocType' can not be set to 'Thick'.
Because read xml node path(FILESYSTEM/AllocType) is fail,
the 'AllocType' value can not be find. Make 'AlloType' always

Change-Id: I63b77b8608b313729159d5732a5dae00cbe67034
Closes-Bug: #1451386
'}, {'created': '2015-05-07 10:47:28.000000000', 'message': "Fix 'AllocType' read failure in Huawei driver

The 'AllocType' have two value: Thin and Thick.
In error code: 'fstype = root.findtext('FILESYSTEM/AllocType')'.
When xml file node path(FILESYSTEM/AllocType) is fail, the 'fstype'
read out is always 'None'. Then code given initial value(Thin).
The 'AllocType' value can not be Thick, even if the 'AllocType' is
set to Thick in configuration file.

Change 'FILESYSTEM/AllocType' to 'Filesystem/AllocType' in
Huawei driver to avoid 'AllocType' can not be read out.

Change-Id: I63b77b8608b313729159d5732a5dae00cbe67034
Closes-Bug: #1451386
"}, {'created': '2015-05-11 02:23:42.000000000', 'message': 'Fix 'AllocType' read failure in Huawei driver

The 'AllocType' have two values: Thin and Thick.
The following piece of code in the Huawei driver has
incorrect path and as a result the 'AllocType' is always
'None'. The correct values should be "Thin" or "Thick"
only.

'fstype = root.findtext('FILESYSTEM/AllocType')'

In code line 366: '"ALLOCTYPE": 1'
The "Thin" is set as the initial value. If the 'AllocType'
is always 'None', the 'AllocType' can not set as "Thick".

Change 'FILESYSTEM/AllocType' to 'Filesystem/AllocType' in
Huawei driver to avoid 'AllocType' can not be read out.

Change-Id: I63b77b8608b313729159d5732a5dae00cbe67034
Closes-Bug: #1451386
'}]
commit_message:
Fix 'AllocType' read failure in Huawei driver

The 'AllocType' have two values: Thin and Thick.
The following piece of code in the Huawei driver has
incorrect path and as a result the 'AllocType' is always
'None'. The correct values should be "Thin" or "Thick"
only.

'fstype = root.findtext('FILESYSTEM/AllocType')'

In code line 366: '"ALLOCTYPE": 1'
The "Thin" is set as the initial value. If the 'AllocType'
is always 'None', the 'AllocType' can not set as "Thick".

Change 'FILESYSTEM/AllocType' to 'Filesystem/AllocType' in
Huawei driver to avoid 'AllocType' can not be read out.

Change-Id: I63b77b8608b313729159d5732a5dae00cbe67034
Closes-Bug: #1451386

commit_message:
load-images: load images via YAML config file

Adds a new load-images python script which can be used to load
multiple images at once using a YAML (or JSON) config file.
Images are actually loaded using the existing load-image script.

The YAML configuration format looks like this (same format
as build-images uses so the YAML config file can be shared):
  disk_images:
    -
    imagename: overcloud-compute
    type: qcow2

Change-Id: I657b6108993ba077c35f1614e7ddd07d1a393a9a

[{'created': '2015-04-15 01:56:44.000000000', 'message': 'devtest_overcloud.sh: split out image building

This patch removes the majority (everything except for the user
image) of image building from devtest_overcloud.sh and provides
a hook to use devtest_overcloud_images.sh or a new build-images
script.

The motivation for this split out was to decrease the complexity
of the devtest_overcloud.sh script while also increasing
the flexability of our devtest_overcloud image building process.

For example:

Some configuration tools (tripleo-image-elements) require that each
role have very specific sets of elements to enable or disable
functionality.

Other configuration tools (puppet) allow image to be built in a variety
of ways. You could use a very minimal base image and install packages
at deployment time. Or alternately you could use images where packages
get pre-installed based on the role. Or you could use just one
image for everything (all the OpenStack packages get pre-installed).

This is an initial step towards making devtest_overcloud.sh
more flexible and configurable with regards to image building.

Change-Id: Idccd180813498401898f10b502106585b1f18eb3

commit_message:
devtest_overcloud.sh: split out image building

This patch removes the majority (everything except for the user
image) of image building from devtest_overcloud.sh and provides
a hook to use devtest_overcloud_images.sh or a new build-images
script.

The motivation for this split out was to decrease the complexity
of the devtest_overcloud.sh script while also increasing
the flexability of our devtest_overcloud image building process.

For example:

Some configuration tools (tripleo-image-elements) require that each
role have very specific sets of elements to enable or disable
functionality.

Other configuration tools (puppet) allow image to be built in a variety
of ways. You could use a very minimal base image and install packages
at deployment time. Or alternately you could use images where packages
get pre-installed based on the role. Or you could use just one
image for everything (all the OpenStack packages get pre-installed).

This is an initial step towards making devtest_overcloud.sh
more flexible and configurable with regards to image building.

Change-Id: Idccd180813498401898f10b502106585b1f18eb3

'}, {'created': '2015-04-23 10:13:56.000000000', 'message': "Always enable DIB debug trace

process and its failures. It adds at max 30% for the number of
log lines, so, it'll not trash our logs.

Change-Id: Iaa69c0fc35f922d35535ee63a9adb6be2d021237
"}, {'created': '2015-05-07 11:44:17.000000000', 'message': "Always enable TRACE in gate for building images

It'll provides us a bunch of additional information to debug
potential issues.

Change-Id: Iaa69c0fc35f922d35535ee63a9adb6be2d021237
"}]
commit_message:
Always enable TRACE in gate for building images

It'll provides us a bunch of additional information to debug
potential issues.

Change-Id: Iaa69c0fc35f922d35535ee63a9adb6be2d021237

commit_message:
Fix comprehension syntax error with python3

When using python3 a couple of comprehensions used in the ipv6 dhcp
code were invalid syntax. This commit fixes them to preserve
functionality but also work with python3.

Change-Id: I3881fe29cb433cd82fd8f190efa0f1fd26419b49

commit_message:
Switch all uses of urllib and HTMLParser to import from six

As part of enabling python3 support in tempest we need to be able to
handle urllib, HTMLParser, and urllib2 usage in both python2 and
python3. Six provides a compat layer for doing this, so this commit
moves all uses of urllib2, HTMLParser, and urllib to get it through
six.

Change-Id: I81e348ac79001ac94bdb92a9b60c7dca4c93686a

commit_message:
Retry logic for insert/delete/update MAC failures

The patch set fixes the problem described in a launchpad
bug, where any failures in inserting/updating/delete MACs
into the OVSDB server do not get retried in a later
point in time. The failure may occur when the L2 gateway
agent is down or the OVSDB server is down.

Change-Id: I79956f498c3279e1c78be812563a32c2c41e77ca
Closes-Bug: 1446805
Closes-Bug: 1451765

commit_message:
rebuild event model only for database writes

we should only build event model when dispatching to database. we
do not need to ensure type-correctness when writing to file or
http.

Change-Id: I553f9062299d7ddcfd0d694aad7a432692bdc953
Closes-Bug: #1438285

commit_message:
cleanup problem events logic in event db storage

when an error occurs in event storage, we capture the errors and
related events but do nothing with it. this patch logs corresponding
errors and raises it if the error is unknown so that dispatcher
can requeue payload.

Change-Id: Id2493b8073646cad9dece626937c8e8af96e1e43

[{'created': '2015-03-14 20:17:09.000000000', 'message': 'Install neutron-lbaas when upgrading from Juno

In Kilo, Neutron LBaaS has been split into its own git repository (neutron-lbaas).  In
Juno it was part of the main neutron repo.  As part of this split, it also implemented
a devstack plugin, delivered under neutron-lbaas/devstack.  This caused the grenade
test to fail when testing the Juno->Kilo upgrade path.

Change-Id: I0b7434af4c5fdbd2b3cfa356c233f0596339d859

commit_message:
Install neutron-lbaas when upgrading from Juno

In Kilo, Neutron LBaaS has been split into its own git repository (neutron-lbaas).  In
Juno it was part of the main neutron repo.  As part of this split, it also implemented
a devstack plugin, delivered under neutron-lbaas/devstack.  This caused the grenade
test to fail when testing the Juno->Kilo upgrade path.

Change-Id: I0b7434af4c5fdbd2b3cfa356c233f0596339d859

HDS HNAS Driver fails when FS unhealthy

This patch fixes the error when there is a file system in an
unhealthy HNAS storage pool.

Change-Id: Ic17c540039996f4a1060829d5f1f12a5f3155271
Closes-bug: #1452002

commit_message:
Remove n-novnc from enabled services

n-novnc caused the job to fails as it was trying to clone
the service from the network, remove this service as its not
really needed

Change-Id: I7b836443ccac2e90fcbd5de97b02da1aaa048ccb

There's no need to load the input data from the database (and it won't be stored the way you think - all of the *inputs* each resource needs are stored in its own row in the SyncPoint table; you'd never query the whole table for *outputs*). The data will arrive in the RPC call telling us to do an update.

It's also preferred that we don't have to modify cfn.functions in order to implement this, since third parties may be creating their own template format plugins and we want those to get convergence features for free. It would be better for Stack.__getitem__ to return some sort of lightweight resource representation with FnGetAtt() and FnGetRefId() methods that return the cached values."}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-03-16 18:27:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-03-16 18:36:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2015-03-16 18:49:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Convergence: Allow creating lightweight stacks

Currently, we load all the resources from the database to resolve
template functions of dependent resources. In convergence, because
every worker will load it's own stack object, loading all the
resources for every resource lifecycle operation will be inefficient.

This patch allows creating lightweight stacks using a cache provided
which will never query the database and only depend on the template
and the cache provided. Function resolutions will now happen by querying
the values in the cache provided if it exists else None is returned.
The resultant lightweight stack will effectively be the stack attributes
loaded from the database and it's raw template with the dependent
resource's functions resolved which will serve as the input for
individual resource objects that will be worked upon.

blueprint convergence-lightweight-stack

Change-Id: I6dbaa7ee4e9d534c31823b4812efcb387c695a22

commit_message:
Remove hyphen from rand_name calls in network tests

data_utils.rand_name() appends randam charactors with a hypen like:

 def rand_name(name=''):
     randbits = str(random.randint(1, 0x7fffffff))
     if name:
         return name + '-' + randbits

So it is not necessary to specify a hypen in caller side.
This patch removes a hypen in network tests.

Change-Id: I1b5c1d3f06f0af38fe13c40d85d456824f8d00d8

[{'created': '2015-04-28 12:42:27.000000000', 'message': 'Log deprecation message when catching deprecated exceptions

When an exception is being deprecated from a library, it is usually
not called anywhere in the user code -- instead it is only caught, so
we never get a chance to see the deprecation message. This patch uses
the fact that an except statement has to do a subclass check on the
exceptions it is trying to catch, and puts the logging code in the
subclass check hook. Unfortunately, that hook has to be defined on the
metaclass, which makes the code a little hard to understand.

Change-Id: Id3cb649343c8d32564e189aecb9aeebe572249cc
'}]
commit_message:
Log deprecation message when catching deprecated exceptions

When an exception is being deprecated from a library, it is usually
not called anywhere in the user code -- instead it is only caught, so
we never get a chance to see the deprecation message. This patch uses
the fact that an except statement has to do a subclass check on the
exceptions it is trying to catch, and puts the logging code in the
subclass check hook. Unfortunately, that hook has to be defined on the
metaclass, which makes the code a little hard to understand.

Change-Id: Id3cb649343c8d32564e189aecb9aeebe572249cc

commit_message:
Sort model fields using getattr(), not inspect()

While inspect(mapping).all_orm_descriptors is a good
way to get at attributes that are known to be mapped or
otherwise described by SQLAlchemy, it does not produce a
SQL expression in the case of a hybrid descriptor, where it
produces the descriptor, not the result of calling it.
This fix ensures that the descriptor is evaulated, while
still retaining the fact that we check the attribute
as coming from an ORM-level descriptor.

Change-Id: I04a03be713348158b8cdfda683624fea01fe34ea
Closes-Bug: #1451880

commit_message:
Fix issue when generating code with cfg.OptGroup

There seems to be an issue when using oslo-config-generator with
cfg.OptGroup.  It seems the generator was not checking if the group
was an object or not.  Resulting in section names as the following:

  [DEFAULT]

  [<oslo_config.cfg.OptGroup object at 0x325c350>]

Change-Id: I946d55fcd713369dda4cdf490391a75901bded22
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>
